<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDENT (APPELLANT), ONTARIO MEDIA DEVELOPMENT CORPORATION</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART 1&mdash;IDENTITY OF APPELLANT, PRIOR COURT &amp; RESULT</TI>
<P>1. The Ontario Media Development Corporation (&ldquo;OMDC&rdquo;) appeals from the judgment of the Divisional Court dated January 25, 2017. The Divisional Court granted the respondent, Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc.'s (&ldquo;Pong Marketing&rdquo;), application for judicial review of the OMDC's decision that 15 &ldquo;casino-style&rdquo; sweepstakes games are ineligible for the Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit (&ldquo;OIDMTC&rdquo;). Pong Marketing's OIDMTC application was remitted back to the OMDC for reconsideration.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART 2&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>2. The OMDC is an agency of Ontario's Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Sport, that was established to promote innovation, investment and employment in Ontario's cultural media industry, and to administer the OIDMTC in furtherance of that objective. To be eligible for the OIDMTC, s. 34(1) of O Reg 37/09 (the &ldquo;Regulation&rdquo;) under the <EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, S.O. 2007 c. 11 Sched A (the &ldquo;Act&rdquo;), requires that a product's primary purpose be to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user.&rdquo; Products that are primarily promotional do not meet the primary purpose test.</P>
<P>3. On its review of Pong Marketing's application, the OMDC found that the primary purpose of Pong Marketing's products are to promote the sale of long-distance telephone calling cards, not to educate, inform or entertain the user. The OMDC assessed the products' primary purpose by reviewing both the developer's intended purpose when developing the sweepstakes games and by analyzing the products from the user's perspective during gameplay.</P>
<P>4. In a split decision, the majority of the Divisional Court held that the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation was unreasonable because it considered the intended purpose of the product when it was being developed. Instead, the majority found that the only reasonable interpretation of the Regulation requires the purpose of the sweepstakes games to be assessed exclusively from the perspective of the user during gameplay. The majority further held, in the alternative, that even if the OMDC's decision was reasonable, the residual presumption applicable to tax legislation would require resolving any ambiguity in the interpretation of the Regulation in favour of the taxpayer.</P>
<P>5. The OMDC submits that although the Divisional Court correctly identified the standard of review as reasonableness, the majority misapplied the standard in their analysis. By failing to consider whether the OMDC's decision falls within a range of possible outcomes, the majority failed to grant deference to the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute and arguably applied a standard of correctness. As held by the dissenting judge, it was reasonable for the OMDC to consider, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the intended purpose of the product at the time of its creation when assessing the primary purpose of the product. The OMDC's decision in this regard is entitled to deference.</P>
<P>6. Moreover, the majority misinterpreted s. 34(1) of the Regulation. The majority's interpretation of the Regulation is too narrow and reads in limitations to the scope of the provision that undermine the legislative intent.</P>
<P>7. Alternatively, even if the majority correctly interpreted s. 34(1) of the Regulation, and assuming that the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute was unreasonable, the OMDC's decision on the respondent's eligibility for the OIDMTC remains reasonable. This is because the majority's decision ignored key evidence showing that the OMDC did in fact consider the promotional content embedded in each sweepstakes game from the users' perspective during gameplay, as required by the majority's interpretation of the provision at issue on the appeal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See paras. 66&ndash;69 in Part 4 of this Factum.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. Finally, and in any event, the majority misapplied the residual presumption to the circumstances of this case. As noted by the dissenting judge, the residual presumption has a &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; role to play in the interpretation of tax legislation and should not apply in a case such as this one where the OMDC's interpretation is reasonable and is supported by the intent and wording of the legislative and regulatory scheme.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Judgment of the Divisional Court, dated January 25, 2017 [&ldquo;Divisional Court Decision&rdquo;], Appeal Book and Compendium of the OMDC [&ldquo;OMDC AB &amp; C&rdquo;], Tab 3, p. 27, paras. 87-88</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. The OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation as allowing it to assess a product's primary purpose by considering both the developer's intention during development and the user's experience during gameplay is reasonable. The OMDC's finding that the purpose of the sweepstakes games is primarily promotional is also justified, transparent and intelligible in light of the evidentiary record before it. For the foregoing reasons, the OMDC's decision warrants deference and its decision should be reinstated.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART 3&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The OMDC and the OIDMTC</TI>
<P>10. The OMDC is an agency of the Ontario Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Sport. It was established in 2000 to promote innovation, investment and employment in Ontario's cultural media industry, and to administer tax credit programs in furtherance of that objective.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 12, para. 2</P1>
<P1>O Reg 672/00, ss. 1, 2, 3, 4, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>11. The OIDMTC is a refundable tax credit for the development of eligible interactive digital media products in Ontario. If a product is eligible for the OIDMTC, the applicant corporation may claim a percentage of its Ontario labour expenditures, and certain marketing and distribution expenditures incurred during the product's development. As a refundable tax credit, the amount of the credit, less any taxes payable, is paid to the corporation.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 12, para. 8</P1></P>
<P>12. The OIDMTC is jointly administered by the OMDC and the Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;). Corporations can submit an application to the OMDC for a Certificate of Eligibility in respect of a product, pursuant to s. 93 of the Act. The OMDC reviews the application, and if the product meets the legislative requirements, the OMDC will issue a Certificate of Eligibility certifying that the product is eligible for the OIDMTC. The corporation can then submit its certificate to the CRA, which conducts an audit and issues a refund in cases where the corporation is entitled to a refund.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 12, para. 2</P1>
<P1><EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, SO 2007 c 11 Sched A, s. 93 (8&ndash;10), Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Legislative Scheme</TI>
<P>13. Pong Marketing's OIDMTC application submitted to the OMDC is governed by s. 93 of the Act, and s. 34 of the Regulation, as it then read.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Section 34(1) of the Regulation has been amended. Effective March 2017, the relevant portion of the amended provision now reads as follows:
<QUOTE><DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo;</TERM> means a combination of one or more application files and one or more data files, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and that have the following characteristics when they are being operated:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>If a qualifying labour expenditure is incurred in respect of the product before April 24, 2015, their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>1.1</N><PARAP>If a qualifying labour expenditure is incurred in respect of the product on or after April 24, 2015 but not before that date, their primary purpose is to entertain the user or to educate users who are under 12 years of age.</PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF></QUOTE></P>
<P>O Reg 37/09, s 34(1). as amended, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. Under s. 93 of the Act, the OMDC is responsible for determining whether a corporation is eligible for the OIDMTC, and whether a product is an eligible product for the OIDMTC.</P>
<P>15. A &ldquo;qualifying corporation&rdquo; must develop an eligible product to qualify for the OIDMTC. Eligible products are defined at s. 93(14) of the Act:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(14)</N><SSECP>In this section,
<DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;eligible product&rdquo;</TERM> means, in respect of a qualifying corporation, a product,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>that satisfies the prescribed conditions or that is a specified product, and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>for which public financial support would not be contrary to the public policy in the opinion of the Ontario Media Development Corporation or, if another person is designated for the purposes of subsection (8), in the opinion of that person.</PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, SO 2007 c 11 Sched A, s. 93(14), Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>16. At the time of Pong Marketing's application, s. 34(1) of the Regulation specified that an eligible product must be an &ldquo;interactive digital media product.&rdquo; Among other requirements, to qualify as an interactive digital media product, the primary purpose of the product was required to either &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>34.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In this section,
<DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo;</TERM> means a combination of one or more application files and one or more data files, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and that have the following characteristics when they are being operated:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>Their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user.</PARAP>
<PARAP>[...]</PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 12, paras. 3-4</P1>
<P1>O Reg. 37/09, s 34(1), Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>17. Furthermore, the Regulation specified that to be eligible for the tax credit, the product could not be &ldquo;used primarily to present, promote, or sell the product or services of the qualifying corporation.&rdquo;
<P1>O Reg 37/09, s 34(3) 6, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Pong Marketing's Application and Game Content</TI>
<P>18. On April 16, 2014, Pong Marketing applied to the OMDC for the OIDMTC (&ldquo;the application&rdquo;). The application concerned 15 sweepstakes games (&ldquo;the sweepstakes games&rdquo;) that Pong Marketing developed between February 2011 and March 2013. The total tax credit being sought by Pong Marketing is approximately $2 million.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 12, paras. 3-4</P1></P>
<P>19. The sweepstakes games are &ldquo;casino-style&rdquo; slot-based games that work by sequentially delivering sweepstakes prizes to the player upon the commitment of &ldquo;sweepstakes points.&rdquo; A player receives sweepstakes points each time he or she purchases a telephone card. A player can also receive points by requesting entry into a game without making a purchase. While the outcome of the game is predetermined, the number of points affects a participant's chance of winning a prize.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 13, para. 16</P1></P>
<P>20. The games are intended to be licensed to third party retailers, including cafe owners, and owners of bars and restaurants, as part of a promotional program to generate revenue. The games are operated through a gaming platform that is licensed to retailers by Pong Marketing.
<P1>Game Document, &ldquo;Amazing 8's&rdquo;, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 6, pp. 37&ndash;47</P1>
<P1>Marketing Document, &ldquo;Amazing 8's&rdquo;, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 7, p. 48</P1></P>
<P>21. Pong Marketing's marketing materials specifically promote their products as being responsive to the market's need for the commercialization of sweepstakes gaming products.
<P1>Marketing Document, &ldquo;Amazing 8's&rdquo;, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 7, p. 48</P1></P>
<P>22. Pong Marketing receives a percentage of revenue generated from the gameplay.
<P1>Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc., &ldquo;Business Model Clarification&rdquo;, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 8, p. 69</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The OMDC Decision</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>The OMDC's Initial Review of Pong Marketing's Application</TI>
<P>23. The OMDC's initial assessment of Pong Marketing's development, licensing and marketing documents was that the sweepstakes games did not qualify for the OIDMTC because it appeared that the products' purpose was primarily promotional. In particular, the OMDC was concerned that the sweepstakes games were produced for the primary purpose of selling long distance telephone cards. The OMDC expressed this concern through correspondence dated July 29, 2015.
<P1>Correspondence through the Online Application Portal [&ldquo;OAP&rdquo;] from OMDC to Pong Marketing, July 29, 2015, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 9, p. 71</P1></P>
<P>24. Pong Marketing's documents were assessed for key factors, including why and how a product was developed, what audience or target market it was developed for, and to whom the product was marketed; this process included a review of Pong Marketing's template licensing agreement, website content, and screenshots of the sweepstakes games themselves.
<P1>Letter from Jennifer Blitz to William Dawson, re &ldquo;OIDMTC Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. 2013 File No. 15214-01-TXM&rdquo; (November 30, 2015), OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 10, p. 81</P1></P>
<P>25. In arriving at its initial decision, the OMDC wrote to Pong Marketing and cited several examples from their application materials that demonstrated the sweepstakes games' primarily promotional purpose. By way of example, the OMDC referred to the manner in which the sweepstakes games and the system through which they are delivered are described in the template licensing agreement filed as part of the application:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>1.0</N><TI>Definitions:</TI>
<P>Delivery System: loyalty platform software...supplied in any way by the Licensor [Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc.] to the Licensee <UNDER>for the use in the sale and promotion of the products or the loyalty program.</UNDER></P>
<P>Sweepstakes Games: <UNDER>A means of promotion to aid in the sale of long distance calling cards and other related products and services</UNDER>.</P>
<P>Sweepstakes Prizes: Any prizes awarded to participants from the Delivery System. [emphasis added]</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE>
<P1>Correspondence through the OAP from, July 29, 2015, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 9, p. 72</P1>
<P1>Template Licencing Agreement&mdash;&ldquo;Amazing 8s&rdquo;, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 11, p. 88</P1></P>
<P>26. The OMDC also referenced material from Pong Marketing's website, which describes sweepstakes games and Pong Marketing's business model in the following terms:
<QUOTE><P>Welcome!</P>
<P>Pong Marketing is a Telecommunication company in the business of delivering a <UNDER>promotional sweepstakes system to enhance the sale of its pre-paid long distance phone time.</UNDER> [emphasis added]</P>
<P>In order to compete against the industries top competitors in the phone card market (i.e., AT&amp;T, Verizon), Pong Marketing has introduced <UNDER>a promotional program that includes sweepstakes games</UNDER>. [emphasis in the OMDC correspondence]</P>
<P>Ideal Solutions</P>
<P>The idea of sweepstakes is to create consumer involvement with a brand or product and <UNDER>thus encourage consumer consumption of the product</UNDER>.</P>
<P>The adoption of interactive video game promotions continues at an extraordinary rate, with <UNDER>more marketers embracing this delivery system for sweepstakes giveaways</UNDER>.</P>
<P>[...]</P>
<P>Advantages 02</P>
<P>Game Promotional Program</P>
<P><BOLD>as a competitive weapon by providing an extra incentive for the target audience to purchase or support one brand over another. In the game promotion program (i.e., sweepstakes), Pong Marketing promotes its telephone cars (sic) (the Tel-Connect calling card) by allowing stores to integrate the sales of its cards with their promotion. This form of marketing acts as an incentive so that the purchase of its card will be favoured over those of its competitors.</BOLD> [emphasis in the OMDC correspondence]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Correspondence through the OAP from, July 29, 2015, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 9, p. 71</P1></P>
<P>27. The OMDC explained to Pong Marketing that to be eligible for the tax credit, the purpose of the product must be primarily to educate, inform or entertain the user. Products deemed to be primarily promotional do not qualify. The OMDC offered Pong Marketing the opportunity to file additional documentation that might address the OMDC's concern that the purpose of the sweepstakes games is primarily promotional.
<P1>Correspondence through the OAP from OMDC to Pong Marketing, July 29, 2015, OMDC AB &amp; C, p. 72</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>Further Documentation Provided by Pong Marketing</TI>
<P>28. Pong Marketing responded to the OMDC's concerns by submitting a document entitled &ldquo;business model clarification.&rdquo; The OMDC reviewed this document and advised Pong Marketing that it did not address the concerns that the OMDC had raised, and in any event, it did not constitute original development documentation. Pong Marketing filed further supporting documentation for review on September 24, 2015, including:
<P1>(a) Game videos from each of the 15 sweepstake games;</P1>
<P1>(b) Pictures from internet cafes where the games were being played;</P1>
<P1>(c) Marketing and game revenue materials</P1>
<P1>(d) A YouTube demonstration video</P1>
<P1>(e) Screen shots from a &ldquo;Pong Studios&rdquo; website.</P1>
<P1>Pong Marketing's Supplementary Filing, filed by Pong Marketing on Sept. 24, 2015, Exhibit Book of the Respondent (Appellant), Tabs 5a, 5b, 5c, 5d and 5e, pp. 518&ndash;697</P1></P>
<P>29. The game videos provided as part of the additional documents allowed the OMDC to view the content embedded in each of the sweepstakes games from the perspective of the user during gameplay. Additional items, such as photos of the venues where the sweepstakes games are operated, and the demonstration video that may be viewed by users, provided additional insight into the products' use from the user's perspective.</P>
<P>30. The OMDC reviewed these materials, and in correspondence dated October 23, 2015, advised Pong Marketing that these documents did not alleviate its concern that the primary purpose of the sweepstakes games is promotional. As part of its reasons, the OMDC cited the prominent in-game promotional content in each of the 15 sweepstakes games that users viewed during gameplay. The reasons provided by the OMDC are as follows:
<P1>(a) There are specific examples from each game product of the prominent in-game promotional content enticing users to purchase additional time for long-distance phone cards;</P1>
<P1>(b) Some of the internet caf&ea; pictures contained long distance phone card signs;</P1>
<P1>(c) Most of the marketing material submitted was not related to the sweepstakes games at issue in the OIDMTC application;</P1>
<P1>(d) The YouTube video contained an animated character that congratulates the user on purchasing a phone card; and</P1>
<P1>(e) With respect to the website, the Pong Studios website screenshots submitted on September 24<SUP>th</SUP> did not match the licencing agreements submitted with the sweepstakes games. The OMDC also noted that the materials from the Pong Marketing website, as of July 2015 and as referenced above, did not match the licencing agreements.</P1>
<P1>Correspondence through the OAP from OMDC to Pong Marketing, Oct. 23, 2015, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 9, pp. 74&ndash;77</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>iii.</N><TI>The OMDC's Determination that the Primary Purpose of the Sweepstakes Games is Promotional</TI>
<P>31. At Pong Marketing's request, the OMDC reviewed the application again. At the conclusion of the review, the OMDC determined that the primary purpose of the sweepstakes games is promotional.
<P1>Letter from OMDC to Pong Marketing, re &ldquo;OIDMTC Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. 2013 File No. 15214-01-TXM&rdquo; (November 30, 2015), OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 10, pp. 81&ndash;86</P1></P>
<P>32. The OMDC issued a formal letter of ineligibility on December 11, 2015. After receipt of this letter, Pong Marketing commenced an application for judicial review seeking, in part, to quash the OMDC's decision.
<P1>Letter from OMDC to Pong Marketing, re &ldquo;OIDMTC Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. [...]&rdquo; (December 11, 2015), OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 4, p. 28</P1>
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 12, para. 7</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>The Divisional Court Decision</TI>
<P>33. The majority of the Divisional Court allowed Pong Marketing's application and remitted the matter back to the OMDC for reconsideration. Writing for the majority, Associate Chief Justice Marrocco (Nordheimer J., concurring) held that the standard of review on the judicial review was reasonableness and that the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation was unreasonable. The majority held that the only reasonable interpretation of s. 34(1) requires the OMDC to look at &ldquo;the primary purpose of the game from the perspective of the player&rdquo; because the section refers to the &ldquo;characteristics of the game when the user is playing it.&rdquo; In ruling that there was only one reasonable interpretation to s. 34(1), the majority effectively applied a correctness standard to the OMDC's interpretation.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 18, para. 37</P1></P>
<P>34. The majority held that any consideration of the developer's motivation for developing the game is irrelevant to the OMDC's assessment of whether the purpose of the sweepstakes games, while in operation, is primarily promotional. This reasoning flows from the majority's literal reading of the definition of &ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo; under the Regulation:
<QUOTE><P>The definition focuses on the time when the application files and data files are operated together by the user <UNDER>and provides that one of their characteristics at that moment is that their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user</UNDER>. The only time the user operates those files is when he or she is playing a Sweepstakes game. The primary purpose of the applicant when creating or licensing the product is a different inquiry. [emphasis original]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 17, paras. 32-33</P1></P>
<P>35. Accordingly, the majority regarded any statements from Pong Marketing's website or template licensing agreement, used as a means of identifying the developer's intention when developing the sweepstakes games, as being unhelpful in determining the primary purpose of the product when it is being operated.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 18, paras. 37-38</P1></P>
<P>36. The majority further held that even if the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) is reasonable, a residual presumption that applies in favour of the taxpayer in the interpretation of taxation statutes should have been applied by the OMDC in this case.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 18, para. 43</P1></P>
<P>37. By contrast, in her dissenting reasons, Justice Sachs would have denied the application. Contrary to the approach taken by the majority, Her Honour held that the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute warranted deference. Justice Sachs held that a reasonable interpretation of the legislation allows the OMDC to consider the purpose for which the product is developed in determining the product's purpose while being operated:
<QUOTE><P>[...] it is not unreasonable when objectively assessing the primary purpose of a product while it is being operated to have regard to what the intended purpose of the product was when it was being developed. After all, it is the product's primary purpose that governs the analysis and it is reasonable to assume that a successfully developed product, when it is being operated, will fulfill the primary purpose for which it was developed.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 26, para. 84</P1></P>
<P>38. Further, Justice Sachs noted that the legislation specifically contemplates that an eligible product may have multiple purposes while it is being operated by the user. As such, it is the OMDC's statutory responsibility to determine the primary purpose of the product. In this case, Her Honour noted that the OMDC is entitled to rely on its review of the sweepstakes games, among other things, to find that the primary purpose of the products while they are being operated is to encourage users to buy calling cards, and not to entertain.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 27 para. 85</P1></P>
<P>39. With respect to the residual presumption, Justice Sachs found that the residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer serves a &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; purpose, and is only applied if it is not possible to resolve the meaning of the legislation using the modem approach to statutory interpretation. In this case, Sachs J. held that the residual presumption has no application as the OMDC resolved the issue without needing to resort to the residual presumption.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 27, paras. 87-88</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART 3&mdash;THE ISSUES</TI>
<P>40. The issues to be determined on this appeal are as follows:
<P1>(a) Did the Divisional Court err in failing to give any deference to the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute, and as such, effectively apply a standard of correctness?</P1>
<P1>(b) Did the Divisional Court err by misinterpreting s. 34(1) of the Regulation such that the scope of the provision is unnecessarily limited?</P1>
<P1>(c) Did the Divisional Court err in failing to give weight to evidence showing that the OMDC did consider the promotional content of the sweepstakes games presented to users while in operation?</P1>
<P1>(d) Did the Divisional Court err in finding that the residual presumption in favour of taxpayers would have any application in this case and that it would favour the respondent?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART 4&mdash;THE LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>The Standard of Review on Appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>41. On an appeal from a decision disposing of an application for judicial review, the question for the appellate court is whether the court below identified the appropriate standard of review and applied it correctly. In <CASEREF><SOC>Merck Frosst Canada Ltd. v Canada (Health)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada described the role of an appellate court in this process as &ldquo;step[ping] into the shoes of the lower court&rdquo; such that the &ldquo;appellate court's focus is, in effect, on the administrative decision.&rdquo; No deference is owed by this court to a decision of the Divisional Court on judicial review.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Agraira v Canada (Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness)</SOC><CITE>2013 SCC 36</CITE><PARANUM>45-46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC Book of Authorities [&ldquo;OMDC BOA&rdquo;], Tab 1</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Merck Frosst Canada Ltd. v Canada (Health)</SOC><CITE>2012 SCC 3</CITE><PARANUM>247</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 2</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of Upper Canada v Abbott</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 525</CITE><PARANUM>93&ndash;96</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 3</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ottawa Police Services v Diafwila</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 627</CITE><PARANUM>50-51</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 4</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>The Majority Erred bv Failing to Grant the OMDC's Decision Any Deference</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. Although the Divisional Court correctly identified the standard of review on the judicial review as reasonableness, the majority's decision misapplies the reasonableness standard when analysing the OMDC's decision. Rather than assessing the OMDC's decision against the principles of justification, transparency and intelligibility to determine whether it falls within a range of possible, acceptable and defensible outcomes that were open to it on the evidence, the majority substituted its own interpretation of the Regulation for that of the OMDC. In this way, the majority effectively applied a standard of correctness and failed to grant the OMDC's decision the deference to which it is entitled.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>Deference should be afforded on a Reasonableness Standard of Review</TI>
<P>43. Both the majority and the dissent correctly identified the standard of review of the OMDC's decision in this case as reasonableness. In so doing, the majority came to the same conclusion as the Divisional Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Venngo Inc. v Ontario Media Development Corp. and Attorney General of Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, which held that the appropriate standard of review for the OMDC's interpretation of the very statutory provision at issue on this appeal is reasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The application in <EM>Venngo</EM> was governed by s. 43.11 of the <EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c C40, and s. 906 of Reg. 183 under the Act, as they then read. The <EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM> and its associated regulation governed applications for the OIDMTC up to and including 2008. Applications for taxation years ending after December 31, 2008, are governed by s. 93 of the <EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM> and s. 34 of O. Reg. 37/09. The relevant provisions are identical.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p.15, para. 24</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Venngo Inc. v Ontario Media Development Corp. and Attorney General of Ontario</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 1036</CITE><COURTJUR>Div Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 1, OMDC BOA, Tab 5</P1></P>
<P>44. Under the reasonableness standard of review, deference is the animating principle. The OMDC's decision can only be considered unreasonable if &ldquo;there is no line of analysis within the given reasons that could reasonably lead the [decision-maker] from the evidence before it to the conclusion at which it arrived.&rdquo; The decision-maker's decision may be reasonable even if its explanation is not one that the reviewing court finds compelling.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>47</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 6 (excerpt)</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] 3 SCR 895</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 7</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 20</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 8</P1></P>
<P>45. This Court has previously warned that it is a &ldquo;grave misconception&rdquo; for reviewing courts to determine the reasonableness of an administrative decision-maker's decision by examining whether it &ldquo;deviates from the correct decision by more than a reasonable margin of error...&rdquo; No single outcome can be regarded as the correct one when examined for reasonableness.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Abdoulrab v Ontario (Labour Relations Board)</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 491</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>46. In the particular context of statutory interpretation, the reviewing court cannot substitute its view of the interpretation and application of the statute for that of the decision-maker's reasonably held view. The Supreme Court of Canada articulated this proposition forcefully in <CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>At the outset it is helpful to contrast judicial review according to the standard of reasonableness with the fundamentally different process of reviewing a decision for correctness. When undertaking a correctness review, the court may undertake its own reasoning process to arrive at the result it judges correct. In contrast, <UNDER>when deciding whether an administrative action was unreasonable, a court should not at any point ask itself what the correct decision would have been.</UNDER> Applying the standard of reasonableness gives effect to the legislative intention that a specialized body will have the primary responsibility of deciding the issue according to its own process and for its own reasons. <UNDER>The standard of reasonableness does not imply that a decision-maker is merely afforded a &ldquo;margin of error&rdquo; around what the court believes is the correct result.</UNDER> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 20</CITE><PARANUM>50</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 8</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>No Deference was granted to the OMDC's Interpretation of the Regulation and Decision</TI>
<P>47. The OMDC is a specialized agency with expertise in the interpretation and application of the relevant statutory provisions of the Act and Regulation. The question of whether the &ldquo;primary purpose&rdquo; of a promotional game is to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo; is at the core of the OMDC's function.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Venngo Inc. v Ontario Media Development Corp. and Attorney General of Ontario</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 1036</CITE><COURTJUR>Div Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 1, OMDC BOA, Tab 5</P1></P>
<P>48. The OMDC determined that the sweepstakes games were developed primarily as promotional vehicles for selling telephone cards. This decision was reasonably made having considered each of the sweepstakes games while in operation from the user's perspective, in addition to the developer's intention when developing the sweepstakes games. This conclusion was intelligible and justified based on the wording of the Regulation, intent of the Act, and the evidentiary record.</P>
<P>49. The majority's decision did not examine whether the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) and its ultimate decision on the application fell within a range of possible outcomes. Instead, the majority substituted their interpretation of s. 34(1) for that of the OMDC, and, as set out below, ignored key evidence showing that the OMDC did consider the promotional content of the products presented to the users while in operation.</P>
<P>50. On its review of the application, the OMDC-concluded that Pong Marketing developed the sweepstakes games to be used as promotional platforms by licensees to promote products to the end user of the game. As found by the OMDC, Pong Marketing's template licensing agreement and website content demonstrates how Pong Marketing anticipated the sweepstakes games would be used by the licensee.</P>
<P>51. Based on the materials submitted, it was reasonable for the OMDC to conclude that the sweepstakes games were designed by Pong Marketing to be used as loyalty platform software by licensees to market their products (i.e., phone cards) to the user.</P>
<P>52. It is important to note that the OMDC's interpretation and application of s. 34(1) does not assume that users cannot be entertained when operating Pong Marketing's products. As noted in Justice Sachs' dissenting reasons, the legislation specifically contemplates that products can serve multiple purposes. However, the Legislature delegated responsibility to the OMDC to use its expertise in the subject matter and in its interpretation of its home statute to administer the tax credit. Where it has done so reasonably, as it has here, the OMDC is entitled to deference.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 27, para. 85</P1></P>
<P>53. By failing to consider whether the OMDC's interpretation was justifiable, transparent, and intelligible based on the materials submitted by Pong Marketing, the majority failed to review the decision on a reasonableness standard and instead effectively applied a standard of correctness. Where the expertise of the OMDC is engaged, as it is here, deference must be granted and respect given to the Legislature's decision to leave such matters in the hands of the OMDC to draw on its particular expertise and experience.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 SCR 190</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 6 (excerpt)</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>The Majority Erred in their Interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation</UNDER></TI>
<P>54. The majority further erred by interpreting s. 34(1) of the Regulation as prohibiting a consideration of the purpose for which the products were developed.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>The Rules of Statutory Interpretation</TI>
<P>55. The Supreme Court of Canada has repeatedly endorsed Driedger's modem approach to statutory interpretation:
<QUOTE><P>[T]he words of an <EM>Act</EM> are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense harmoniously with the scheme of the <EM>Act</EM>, the object of the <EM>Act</EM>, and the intention of Parliament.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Elmer A. Driedger, <EM>Construction of Statutes</EM>, 2nd ed. (Toronto: Butterworths, 1983) at p. 87, OMDC BOA, Tab 10 (excerpt)</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership v Rex</SOC><CITE>[2002] SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 11 (excerpt)</P1></P>
<P>56. The modem approach to statutory interpretation requires the court to: (i) examine the words of the provision in their ordinary and grammatical sense; (ii) consider the entire context that the provision is located within; and (iii) consider whether the proposed interpretation produces a just and reasonable result.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership v Rex</SOC><CITE>[2002] SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 11 (excerpt)</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bapoo v Co-operators General Insurance Co</SOC><CITE>[1997] OJ No 5055</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 12</P1></P>
<P>57. The factors comprising the &ldquo;entire context&rdquo; include the history of the provision at issue, its place in the overall scheme of the Act, the object of the Act itself, and the Legislature's intent in enacting the Act as a whole and the particular provision at issue. A just and reasonable result promotes applications of the Act that advance its purpose and avoids applications that are &ldquo;foolish and pointless.&rdquo;
<P1>Pierre-Andr&ea; C&oc;t&ea;, <EM>The Interpretation of Legislation in Canada</EM>, 3rd ed. at p. 387, OMDC BOA, Tab 13 (excerpt)</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>The Majority's Interpretation of s. 34(1) is Too Narrow</TI>
<P>58. At the time of the application, s. 34(1) of the Regulation read as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>34.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In this section,</SSECP>
<SSECP>&ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo; means a combination of one or more application files and one or more data files, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and that have the following characteristics when they are being operated:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP><UNDER>Their</UNDER> primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user.</PARAP>
<PARAP>[...]</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1>O. Reg. 37/09, s. 34(1), Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>59. For the majority, the central concern with interpreting s. 34(1) as allowing a consideration of the developer's purpose, as favoured by the OMDC, is that the &ldquo;developer's fundamental purpose&rdquo; may weigh negatively against their eligibility for the tax credit. This, they held, is inconsistent with the Legislature's intention to use the tax credit to assist high technology, knowledge-based industries. The majority interpreted s. 34(1) as avoiding this problem by focusing instead on the characteristics of the product from the subjective perspective of the user while the user plays the game. Respectfully, this interpretation is too narrow.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, pp. 17-18, paras 35 and 37</P1></P>
<P>60. When read in its entire context and in the grammatical and ordinary sense, s. 34(1) does not prohibit consideration of the purpose for which a product is developed. It is evident on a plain reading of s. 34(1) that this provision can be interpreted to include the purpose for which the product was developed. The reference to &ldquo;they&rdquo; in &ldquo;when <UNDER>they</UNDER> are being operated ... <UNDER>Their</UNDER> primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo;, is a reference to the product's purpose and not the user's purpose. The user's purpose will always be subjective. Users may play games to be entertained or to benefit from the products the games promote, or both. But the developer's purpose in developing the products can be ascertained from the sweepstakes games, licensing agreements, and promotional materials, and is necessarily relevant to determining the sweepstakes games' overall purpose while they are being operated.</P>
<P>61. Additionally, focus on the purpose for which the sweepstakes games were developed is more consistent with the purpose for which the OIDMTC is made available. Contrary to the majority's premise, and as correctly identified in the dissenting reasons, the tax credit is intended to facilitate growth in the cultural media sector and not the interactive digital media industry writ large. Determining whether a product is eligible for the OIDMTC is a task that has been delegated to the OMDC the OMDC's mandate is to &ldquo;foster the development and enhancement of the cultural media industry in Ontario.&rdquo; This mandate is not meant to create jobs in the digital media industry generally, but rather to &ldquo;create jobs in particular sectors&rdquo; of that industry.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 25, para. 77</P1></P>
<P>62. For this reason, the Regulation requires an assessment of the product's purpose to ensure that it is intended primarily to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user.&rdquo; If the intention was simply to create jobs through a broadly administered tax credit, then all interactive digital media products, and in particular all digital interactive games, regardless of their predominant purpose, would qualify. This is not what the Legislature intended.</P>
<P>63. Viewed in this way, there is a logical link between a product developer's intention and the end product's operation. As stated by Sachs J. in dissent, it is &ldquo;reasonable to assume that a product when operated successfully will fulfill the primary purpose for which it was developed.&rdquo; When the primary purpose of a product is the focal point for determining eligibility for a tax credit, it is reasonable to refer to the developer's intention as the OMDC did in this case.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 26, para. 84</P1></P>
<P>64. Accordingly, the OMDC considered both the developer's purpose when designing the sweepstakes game and its intended use while in operation by the user. Both of these factors were considered by the OMDC to determine the product's primary purpose. The OMDC reasonably concluded that the sweepstakes games were designed with the expectation that they would be used by licensees to promote the sale of telephone cards to the end users of the games. The OMDC reached this conclusion based on Pong Marketing's application materials, as described above.</P>
<P>65. By focusing on the subjective purpose for which a user may play one of the sweepstakes games, the majority interpreted s. 34(1) too narrowly and without reference to the wording of the provision as a whole and the purpose of the OIDMTC.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI><UNDER>No Consideration Given to the OMDC's Review of the Promotional Content of the Sweepstakes Games Presented to Users While in Operation</UNDER></TI>
<P>66. In the alternative, even if the majority was correct that the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) was unreasonable and the product developer's motivation for developing a product is an irrelevant consideration, the OMDC's decision is still reasonable.</P>
<P>67. The majority held that the only reasonable interpretation of the provision involves an assessment of the product from the user's perspective during gameplay and that any consideration of the developer's intention when developing the game is irrelevant to the primary purpose analysis. Even if the majority correctly interpreted s. 34(1), the majority failed to consider key evidence that the OMDC <UNDER>did</UNDER> consider the user's perspective during gameplay in carrying out the primary purpose analysis.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 17, para. 33</P1></P>
<P>68. In its correspondence to Pong Marketing, the OMDC details its observations regarding the promotional content embedded in each of the sweepstakes games as it appears to users during gameplay. The predominant nature of the promotional content identified by the OMDC includes, among other things, popup bubbles enticing users to add additional time to their telephone card accounts by purchasing more play time, and graphic images of buttons requesting users to &ldquo;Buy $1 More Time&rdquo;, designed to be visible to users during the entire duration of regular (non-bonus) gameplay.
<P1>Correspondence through the OAP from October 23, 2015, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 9, pp. 74&ndash;76. <BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This citation contains the full list of embedded promotional content identified by the OMDC in each of the 15 sweepstakes games.</P1></P>
<P>69. It is abundantly clear from the record that the OMDC's primary purpose analysis did consider the products as at the time that &ldquo;the user is playing it&rdquo; and not only at the &ldquo;moment it is created or licensed.&rdquo; This error was fundamental to the majority's decision.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 18, para. 37</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI><UNDER>No Residual Presumption Applies in the Circumstances of the Present Case</UNDER></TI>
<P>70. The majority further erred in finding that the residual presumption in favour of taxpayers would have any application in this case and that it would favour Pong Marketing. The Supreme Court of Canada has held that the residual presumption has a limited purpose and must only be applied in &ldquo;exceptional&rdquo; cases where application of the modem approach to statutory interpretation does not resolve the meaning of the legislation. The present case is not one where the residual presumption applies.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>The Residual Presumption Applies only in Exceptional Circumstances</TI>
<P>71. There is no longer any rule of statutory interpretation that requires ambiguities in tax related statutes to be read in favour of taxpayers. If there are two interpretations, the more reasonable one must prevail. Where there are two interpretations and one cannot be said to be the more reasonable than the other, the choice should then be resolved in favour of the taxpayer. The existence of competing interpretations alone does not establish ambiguity.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC><CITE>[2006] 1 SCR 715</CITE><PARANUM>21&ndash;24</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 14</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ontario Cancer Institute (c.o.b. Princess Margaret Hospital) v Ontario (Minister of Revenue)</SOC><CITE>[1997] OJ No 3446</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Ct. (Gen Div.)</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 59, OMDC BOA Tab 15</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>TimberWest Forest Corp. v Campbell</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 102</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 16</P1></P>
<P>72. As such, the application of the residual presumption is necessarily limited to &ldquo;exceptional&rdquo; circumstances. In <CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</EM>&rdquo;), the Supreme Court of Canada explained the limitation of the residual presumption as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[...] first, recourse to the presumption in the taxpayer's favour is indicated when a court is compelled to choose between two valid interpretations, and second, this <UNDER>presumption</UNDER> is <UNDER>clearly residual</UNDER> and should play an exceptional part in the interpretation of tax legislation. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</SOC><CITE>[1994] 3 SCR 3</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 17</P1></P>
<P>73. More recently, in <CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court cited <EM>Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</EM> with approval and confirmed the exceptional role that the residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer plays in the interpretation of taxation statutes:
<QUOTE><P>[...] Any doubt about the meaning of a taxation statute must be reasonable, and no recourse to the presumption lies unless the usual rules of interpretation have been applied, <UNDER>to no avail</UNDER>, in an attempt to discern the meaning of the provision at issue. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC><CITE>[2006] 1 SCR 715</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 14</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>There is No Ambiguity in the Interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation Warranting Application of the Residual Presumption</TI>
<P>74. The majority erred in their application of the residual presumption in the circumstances of this case. In their reasons, the majority declined to resort to the residual presumption because they found on an application of the modem approach to statutory interpretation that the OMDC's interpretation of the Regulation was unreasonable.</P>
<P>75. The majority held, in the alternative, that even if the OMDC's decision were reasonable, the application of the residual presumption requires the OMDC to apply the reasonable interpretation of the Regulation which is more favourable to the taxpayer.
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 18, para. 43</P1></P>
<P>76. In this circumstance, the application of the residual presumption is incongruent with the principles governing judicial review on a reasonableness standard of review.</P>
<P>77. In <CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court held that where there are two reasonable competing interpretations of a decision-maker's home statute, the reviewing court must side with the decision-maker:
<QUOTE><P>The bottom line here, then, is that the Commission holds the interpretative upper hand: under reasonableness review, we defer to <UNDER>any</UNDER> reasonable interpretation adopted by an administrative decision maker, <UNDER>even if</UNDER> other reasonable interpretations may exist. Because the legislature charged the administrative decision maker rather than the courts with &ldquo;administer[ing] and apply[ing]&rdquo; its home statute (<EM>Pezim</EM>, at p. 596), it is the decision maker, first and foremost, that has the discretion to resolve a statutory uncertainty by adopting any interpretation that the statutory language can reasonably bear. Judicial deference in such instances is itself a principle of modem statutory interpretation. [emphasis original]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] 3 SCR 895</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>78. Because deference is owed to the decision-maker on a reasonableness standard, Pong Marketing has the high burden of proving not only that its interpretation is reasonable, but that OMDC's interpretation is <EM>unreasonable</EM>. The Supreme Court framed the burden as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Accordingly, the appellant's burden here is not only to show that her competing interpretation is reasonable, but also that the [decision-maker's] interpretation is <EM>unreasonable</EM>. And that she has not done. Here, the [decision-maker], with the benefit of its expertise, chose the interpretation it did. And because that interpretation has not been shown to be an unreasonable one, there is no basis for us to interfere on judicial review&mdash;even in the face of a competing reasonable interpretation. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] 3 SCR 895</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, OMDC BOA, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>79. In the present case, the majority's resort to the residual presumption in a circumstance where the OMDC's decision is assumed to be reasonable is at odds with both the principles underlying the residual presumption, as well as the well-established administrative law principles guiding the standard of reasonableness.</P>
<P>80. If the OMDC's decision is reasonable, then by definition there is no ambiguity in the interpretation of the legislation requiring resort to the residual presumption; it is necessarily implied that no unresolvable dispute exists regarding the meaning of the provision. As such, the decision-maker's interpretation falls within a range of possible outcomes and is thus owed deference.</P>
<P>81. For the foregoing reasons, Sachs J. properly disagreed with the majority's reliance on the residual presumption as an alternative. Upon restating the &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; role played by the residual presumption, Sachs J. held that because the OMDC was able to ascertain a reasonable interpretation of s. 34(1), the presumption has no application in this case and should not be applied in favour of Pong Marketing. In her dissent, Sachs J. writes:
<QUOTE><P><CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v. Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon-Secours</SOC><CITE>1994 CanLII 58</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1994] 3 S.C.R. 3</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>171 N.R. 161</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> and the cases that have followed it have made it clear that the presumption at issue now has a very limited role to play in the interpretation of tax legislation. It is a residual presumption that should only be resorted to if it is not possible to resolve the meaning of the legislation by applying Driedger's modem approach to statutory interpretation. In this case, the OMDC was able to resolve the meaning of the legislation in question without resort to the residual presumption. A reasonableness review requires that the OMDC's decision in this regard be respected unless it falls outside the range of possible and acceptable outcomes.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Divisional Court Decision, OMDC AB &amp; C, Tab 3, p. 27, para. 88</P1></P>
<P>82. As noted above, the majority erroneously stated that the residual presumption would apply in Pong Marketing's favour if the OMDC's interpretation of the Regulation were found to be reasonable. This statement conflicts with the scope of the reviewing court's authority on a reasonableness standard of review and does not give rise to the exceptional circumstances necessary to apply the residual presumption.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART 5&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>83. The OMDC respectfully requests:
<P1>(a) An order dismissing the application;</P1>
<P1>(b) The costs of this appeal and the underlying motion for leave to appeal; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
