<BLOCK0><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDENT IN APPEAL, PONG MARKETING AND PROMOTIONS INC.</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW&mdash;NATURE OF CASE AND ISSUES</TI>
<P>1. In its factum, the Ontario Media Development Corporation (&ldquo;the Appellant&rdquo; or &ldquo;the OMDC&rdquo;) seeks to complicate a very simple case. The majority in the Divisional Court applied the appropriate standard of review: reasonableness. And it reached the appropriate result: the OMDC's interpretation of the relevant provision is unreasonable. That should be the beginning and end of the matter.</P>
<P>2. Instead, the OMDC tries to circumvent the Divisional Court's unassailable reasoning in two respects. First, the ODMC contends that, although the majority was unequivocal that it had reviewed the OMDCs decision on the basis of reasonableness, in actuality the Divisional Court applied a correctness standard. In so doing, the OMDC effectively invents a ground of appeal out of whole cloth. The OMDC's real complaint is not that the Divisional Court failed to accord it deference. The OMDC's problem is that the Divisional Court did not apply the reasonableness standard as though it were a rubber stamp. That is not a legal error.</P>
<P>3. Second, the OMDC contends that the majority in the Divisional Court misapplied the residual presumption which favours the taxpayer in the interpretation of a tax benefit. But Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O. was abundantly clear that he <EM>did not apply the residual presumption at all</EM>. In fact, his exact words were: <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;I do not find it necessary to resort to this principle to resolve this application because I do not think the respondent's interpretation is a reasonable one.&rdquo;</EM></BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Judgment of the Divisional Court dated January 25, 2017 [&ldquo;Divisional Court's Reasons&rdquo;], at para. 43 [Appeal Book and Compendium (&ldquo;AB&amp;C&rdquo;), at Tab 3, pp. 18-19]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> One can't misapply what one hasn't applied in the first place. Even if the residual presumption were engaged, the approach now attacked would have been correct. Reasonableness and deference are not intended to insulate an administrative decision-maker from the principles of interpretation that govern every other tribunal or court.</P>
<P>4. Accordingly, and pursuant to the below, the Respondent requests that the appeal be dismissed.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<P>5. The Respondent accepts the Appellant's summary of the facts as substantially correct and relies on the following additional facts.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Pong's Business Model</EM></TI>
<P>6. Pong Game Studios Corporation (previously Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc.) (&ldquo;Pong&rdquo; or &ldquo;the Respondent&rdquo;) is a digital studio based in Woodbridge, Ontario that designs interactive digital games. The Respondent's library of games includes the fifteen &ldquo;sweepstakes&rdquo; games at issue here (&ldquo;the Gaming Products&rdquo;). These games resemble slot-machine type games in which the player typically has a number of spins. The Gaming Products have creative designs and unique themes that make them fun for the user.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Descriptions of the Gaming Products, including pictures, may be found in the OMDC's Exhibit Book [&ldquo;OMDC's EB&rdquo;], at Tab 3, pp. 63&ndash;515</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. Pong obtains revenue from the Gaming Products by licensing them to third parties, such as telecommunication companies. These third parties use the Gaming Products to promote their own products. Because Pong's games are entertaining for the user to play, they are conducive to providing this promotional opportunity. That is always going to be the case with digital games. As the producers of The Price is Right (or any other game show) would attest, games that are entertaining tend to serve as a good vehicle for promotion.</P>
<P>8. All of Pong's revenue, however, is derived from having users play and enjoy the game. Entertainment is therefore Pong's focus; promotion potential is secondary and completely under the control of the third-party licensee.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Digital Media Tax Credit</EM></TI>
<P>9. The Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit (&ldquo;Digital Media Tax Credit&rdquo;) was introduced in 1998. The Digital Media Tax Credit is a refundable tax credit for up to 40% of eligible Ontario labour, marketing, and distribution expenditures incurred through the development of interactive digital media products that educate, inform, or entertain the user.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, S.O. 2007 c. 11 Sched. A [&ldquo;<EM>Taxation Act</EM>&rdquo;], s. 93(2.1) and s. 93(14); O. Reg. 37/09 [&ldquo;the Regulations&rdquo;], s. 34(1). As the OMDC notes in its factum (see at p. 4, n.3), effective March 2017 the legislature has amended s. 34(1) of the Regulations in order to restrict eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit. Prior to the amendment, an &ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo; was defined as a product whose primary purpose was to &ldquo;educate, inform, or entertain the user.&rdquo; The definition has changed so that &ldquo;interactive digital media products&rdquo; are now those that &ldquo;entertain the user or ... educate users who are under 12 years of age.&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Digital Media Tax Credit was designed to create &ldquo;good-paying jobs in the high-tech industries&rdquo; such as interactive digital media.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario, legislative Assembly, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 36th Parl, 2nd Sess, No L064B (3 Dec 1998) at 2020 (Bert Johnson) [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 1, p. 2]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The aim behind the Digital Media Tax Credit was thus to &ldquo;help businesses in these industries grow and contribute to the development of long-term, internationally viable Ontario industries with jobs for the future.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario, Legislative Assembly, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 36th Parl, 2nd Sess, No L064B (3 Dec 1998) at 2120 (Bert Johnson) [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 1, p. 23]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Digital Media Tax Credit was expanded in 2006, 2008, and 2009 with the aim to &ldquo;encourage individuals to invest&rdquo; in the area of digital media.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Ontario, Legislative Assembly, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 38th Parl, 2nd Sess, No L116A (31 Oct 2006) at 1630 (Hon Michael A Brown) [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 2, p. 27]. See also Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 12 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 13]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong is one such enterprise.</P>
<P>10. Pursuant to s. 34(1) of the Regulations, a &ldquo;non-specified&rdquo; product may be eligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit if it is &ldquo;an interactive digital media product&rdquo; and the product is not captured by one of the listed exceptions in s. 34(3). Subsection 34(3) In relevant part provides:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(3)</N><SSECP>A product... is an eligible product for [a credit] if the following conditions are satisfied:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>The product is an interactive digital media product. ...</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>5.</N><PARAP>The product is not used <UNDER>primarily to present or promote</UNDER> <UNDER>the qualifying corporation</UNDER> or a qualifying predecessor corporation.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>6.</N><PARAP>The product is not used <UNDER>primarily to present, promote or sell the products or services of the qualifying corporation</UNDER> or of a qualifying predecessor corporation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Emphasis added. Note s. 34(3) has also been amended as of March 2017, but the quoted portions are unchanged.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>11. Accordingly, an interactive digital media product will not be eligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit if its primary use is to promote <EM>the applicant</EM> or <EM>the applicant's products</EM>. That is not the same as a product purchased or leased by a third party. The provision contains no reference to the promotion of a third party's products.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The OMDC's Guidelines and the evolution of the Digital Media Tax Credit</EM></TI>
<P>12. The OMDC has published Guidelines related to the Digital Media Tax Credit which explain, among other things, how eligibility for the credit is determined.</P>
<P>13. The Guidelines as they existed at the time of Pong's application clearly indicated that the Gaming Products would be eligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit. Quoting from the Regulations, the Guidelines stated that an interactive digital media product would qualify provided that it did not promote the applicant's own products.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit Guidelines (updated June 2011) [&ldquo;the Guidelines&rdquo;], at pp. 6, 13&ndash;19 [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 3, pp. 36, 43&ndash;49]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. The OMDC updated the Guidelines in or around June 2015 in light of proposed amendments to the Regulations (which ultimately went into effect in March 2017). The amended Guidelines provided additional clarity to the eligibility requirements. The amended Guidelines explained that products would be considered primarily promotional and ineligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit <EM>unless they had a &ldquo;revenue generating stream&rdquo;</EM>. According to the OMDC, revenue generating streams include:
<ITEM><P>The sale of the product;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD>Fees for use of the product, including licence and subscription fees; In-product purchases (also called an in-game or in-app purchase, which occurs when the user can purchase an enhancement to the product);</BOLD></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD>Third party advertising within the product (marketing and promotion of a corporation or person, or products or services of a corporation or person, that is not related to the product developer or the purchaser corporation in the case of a specified product);</BOLD> and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The sale or licence of another product developed by your company that can reasonably be considered an extension or upgrade of the product.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit Guidelines (updated June 2015) [&ldquo;the amended Guidelines&rdquo;], at p. 14 (emphasis added) [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 4, p. 114]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></ITEM></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Application of the Digital Media Tax Credit to other digital media companies</EM></TI>
<P>15. In light of these Guidelines, the OMDC has granted entitlement to the Digital Media Tax Credit to companies that, like Pong, produce digital games that promote the products of third-party licensees. Fuel Industries (&ldquo;Fuel&rdquo;) is one example. Fuel has benefitted from at least $3 million in credits from the OMDC.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario, Legislative Assembly, Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 41st Parl, 1st Sess, F-9 (22 January 2015) (Hon Sue Wong) at F-144. (See generally F-142-44) [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 5, p. 178 (see generally pp. 176&ndash;178)]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> According to its website, Fuel &ldquo;helps Fortune 500 global brands connect with GenZ, Millennial and Family audiences using deep, digital brand experiences that include immersive virtual worlds, mobile apps and social gaming, branded entertainment, interactive multi-screen experiences, interactive rich media advertising, and digital loyalty programs.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fuel Industries, &ldquo;About&rdquo;, online: <UNDER>http://www.fuelyouth.com/about</UNDER> [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 6A, p. 221]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Fuel's games include such offerings as <EM>NASCAR: Acceleration Nation, Disney Junior Magic Phone, DreamWorks DreamPlace: Naughty or Nice</EM>, and <EM>McDonald's: Cut the Rope</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fuel Industries, &ldquo;Work&rdquo;, online: <UNDER>http://www.fuelyouth.com/work</UNDER> [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 6B, pp. 226&ndash;231] &tilde;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Fuel boasts that one of its games, available through McDonald's &ldquo;Magic Camera&rdquo; application, &ldquo;led to a 500% increase of the Magic Camera app downloads vs the previous month.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fuel Industries, &ldquo;How to Train Your Dragon 2&rdquo;, online: <UNDER>http://www.fuelyouth.com/projects/how-to-train-your-dragon-2/</UNDER> [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 6C, p. 233]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. Fuel was undoubtedly awarded eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit because its games are designed for entertainment and its products have an independent revenue generating stream. In addition, the (extensive) promotional content in Fuel's games is not aimed at promoting Fuel's <EM>own</EM> products, but rather the products of third parties. Fuel, like Pong, is therefore not excluded by any of the listed exceptions in s. 34(3).</P>
<P>17. Nor is Fuel the only similarly-situated company that the OMDC has deemed eligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Ontario, Legislative Assembly, Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 41st Parl, 1st Sess, F-11 (27 January 2015) (Hon Sue Wong) at F-236-37. BattleGoat Studios and SHGStudios (f/k/a Snakehead Games) are also listed as recipients of the Digital Media Tax Credit. [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 7, pp. 251-252]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Pong's Application for the Digital Media Tax Credit</EM></TI>
<P>18. Pong applied for the Digital Media Tax Credit for the Gaming Products on April 16, 2014. Pong sought a tax credit of approximately $2 million. The claimed amount represented the work of over 60 Pong game developers, testers, mathematicians, and designers, constituting 90% of Pong's employees at the time.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 4 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 12]; see also Letter from T. Gioia to K. Thorne-Stone dated Nov. 3, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 14, p. 725]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. Pong expended significant resources developing the Gaming Products on the perfectly reasonable expectation that it was entitled to the Digital Media Tax Credit according to the plain language of the relevant provision and the OMDC's Guidelines. Pong was anxious to receive these funds in order to reinvest in its business and employ additional people at its Wood bridge facility.</P>
<P>20. Pong did not receive an answer from the OMDC until more than <EM>15 months</EM> after Pong submitted its application. In the meantime, it continued to support high-tech jobs in its facility. On July 29, 2015, Michael Olivier, the Business Officer assigned to the file, informed Pong's CEO William Dawson of the OMDC's position that &ldquo;all of the[] games are primarily promotional, as they were developed expressly as sweepstakes promotions for long distance phone cards.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through the OMDC Online Application Portal (&ldquo;OAP&rdquo;) between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated July 29, 2015. [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 711] (Pursuant to OMDC policy, much of the correspondence between Pong and the OMDC took place through the OAP.)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. Mr. Oliver stated that the OMDC's position was based on two things. First, Mr. Olivier cited Pong's statements on its website that Pong's products were designed to help telecommunication companies compete &ldquo;against the industry's] top competitors in the phone card market&rdquo; and &ldquo;create consumer involvement with a brand or product and thus encourage consumption of that product.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated July 29, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 711]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Second, Mr. Olivier claimed that Pong's template licensing agreement &ldquo;confirmed] the promotional nature of the submitted sweepstakes games&rdquo; because, for example, the licensing agreement stated that Pong's games could be used as a &ldquo;means of promotion to aid in the sale of long distance calling cards and other related products or services.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W, Dawson and M. Olivier dated July 29, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 712]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. Pong was surprised and disappointed by the OMDC's position. On September 8, 2015, Mr. Dawson submitted a further correspondence to the OMDC in which he attempted to explain that the OMDC had conflated the products' purpose with Pong's business model. Mr. Dawson agreed that one of Pong's revenue models was to licence its games &ldquo;to the game promotion/sweepstakes market.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated September 8, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 4A, p. 516]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, &ldquo;[i]n this licensed revenue stream, <EM>a game player's sole interest is to be entertained by the games played</EM> with a prospect of winning a prize.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated September 8, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 4A, p. 516] (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mr. Dawson pointed out that &ldquo;[t]he recent budget amendments <EM>require</EM> a revenue generating stream in an attempt to eliminate promotional products from&rdquo; eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated September 8, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 4A, p. 517] (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As Mr. Dawson added, &ldquo;Pong's products clearly meet this definition as they have always been for sale via the license agreement&rdquo; and they are &ldquo;not used primarily to present, promote or sell the products or services of the qualifying corporation or of a qualifying predecessor corporation.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated September 8, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 4A, p. 517]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mr. Dawson stated that he was available for further discussion or clarification and suggested a site visit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through GAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated Sept. 8, 2015, 3:57pm [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 719]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. Less than two hours later, Mr. Olivier responded that &ldquo;I don't read anything in your Business Model clarification document that changes our primary purpose determination&rdquo; and a &ldquo;face to face meeting is not warranted at this time.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between M. Olivier and W. Dawson dated Sept. 8, 2015, 5:52pm [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 719]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. Mr. Dawson provided additional documentation on September 24, 2015 consisting of screen captures from Pong's website, game revenue by title from April 1, 2012 through March 31, 2015, pictures of internet cafe game rooms, marketing materials, and game videos.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated Sept. 24, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, pp. 718-19]; see also Additional Documents Provided by Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. on September 24, 2015. [OMDC's EB, at Tab 5, pp. 518&ndash;697]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. Mr. Olivier responded on October 23, 2015 that he had reviewed the games and the additional documentation and had not changed his mind. Among other things, Mr. Olivier stated that he had noticed that the games contained in-game promotional content for phone cards.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between M. Olivier and W. Dawson of October 23, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, pp. 714-18]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. Pong followed up with a letter through counsel on November 3, 2015. The letter again emphasized that &ldquo;the primary purpose of {the Gaming Products] is to entertain the user&rdquo; and that each of the Gaming Products &ldquo;contains an individual revenue generating stream&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from T. Gioia to K. Thorne-Stone dated November 3, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 14, pp. 725-26]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. Jennifer Blitz, the OMDC's Director of Tax Credits and Financing Programs, responded on behalf of the OMDC on November 30, 2015. Ms. Blitz confirmed the OMDC's position that the Gaming Products were ineligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit because they promoted the products of third-party licensees. Ms. Blitz again referred to Pong's licensing agreement and website. She also cited the in-game promotional content.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from J. Blitz to W. Dawson dated November 30, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 15, pp. 727-32]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. On December 11, 2015, almost <EM>twenty months</EM> after Pong submitted its application, the OMDC issued a Letter of Ineligibility for the Gaming Products. The letter stated, in conclusory terms, that the products did not satisfy s. 34(f) of the Regulations because their primary purpose was not to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo;, but rather &ldquo;to promote the sale of phonecards and other related products and services.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from J. Blitz to W. Dawson dated December 11, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 19, p. 755]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;POSITION ON ISSUES</TI>
<P>29. The Appellant proposes four issues.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellant's Factum, at para. 40</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Properly understood, this appeal presents the following questions:
<P1>(a) Was the OMDC's interpretation of the relevant provision unreasonable?</P1>
<P1>(b) Did the Divisional Court apply the appropriate standard of review?</P1>
<P1>(c) Does the residual presumption apply in this case?</P1></P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>The OMDC's Interpretation of s. 34(1) is Unreasonable</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The OMDC's application of the Digital Media Tax Credit conflicts with the plain language and purpose of the relevant provision</EM></TI>
<P>30. The Appellant argues that the Divisional Court's interpretation of s. 34(1) &ldquo;is too narrow and reads in limitations to the scope of the provision that undermine the legislative intent.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Appellant's Factum at paras. 6, 65</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> With respect, this is the pot calling the kettle black. The Divisional Court's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulations is the only reasonable interpretation available in light of the plain language of the provision and the object and purpose behind the Digital Media Tax Credit. In contrast, the OMDC's interpretation is ungrounded in the words of the Regulations and calculated to contrive an overly restrictive reading that clashes with the language of the provision and its legislative purpose.</P>
<P>31. The Divisional Court examined the plain language of s. 34(1), which defines an &ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo; as:
<QUOTE><P>... <EM>a combination of</EM> one or more <EM>application files</EM> and one or more <EM>data files</EM>, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and <EM>that have the following characteristics when they are being operated</EM>:</P>
<P>1. <UNDER><EM>Their</EM></UNDER> primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 26 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 16] (underlining added by Divisional Court; other emphasis added).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>32. The Divisional Court pointed out that the &ldquo;their&rdquo; in s. 34(1) of the Regulations obviously refers to the &ldquo;application files&rdquo; or the &ldquo;data files&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 27 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 16]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Put simply, the provision indicates that a digital game will be an eligible interactive digital media product if the primary purpose of <BOLD><EM>the game, while It is being played</EM>,</BOLD> is to entertain <BOLD><EM>the user</EM>.</BOLD> No other reasonable reading of the Regulations is credibly available. Had the Regulation intended to focus on the developer, it could have, and would have, said so. It does not and the language used is unambiguous.</P>
<P>33. As the Divisional Court summarized:
<QUOTE><P>The definition focuses on the time when the application files and data files are operated together by the user and provides that one of their characteristics at that moment is that their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user. The only time the user operates those files is when he or she is playing a Sweepstakes game. The primary purpose of the applicant when creating or licensing the product is a different inquiry.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 33 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 17]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>34. In addition to emphasizing the unambiguous language of the provision, the Divisional Court explained why the OMDC's interpretation clashes with the object and purpose behind the Digital Media Tax Credit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 35 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 17]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. As set out above, the OMDC felt that the primary purpose of the Gaming Products was not to entertain the user because the games were designed to, among other things, &ldquo;help licensees or retailers compete against top competitors in the phone card market&rdquo; and &ldquo;create consumer involvement with a brand or product to encourage consumption of that product.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 30 {AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 17] quoting Correspondence through OAP from M. Olivier to W. Dawson of July 29, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 711]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. That reading of the provision is simply unreasonable and ungrounded in the words. Whatever measure of deference one offers to the OMDC, at some point words have obvious meanings that must be respected.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <CASEREF><SOC>Canada v. Antosko</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 S.C.R. 312</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Pong's Book of Authorities (&ldquo;Pong's BOA&rdquo;), at Tab 1] (&ldquo;While it is true that the courts must view discrete sections of [taxation legislation] in light of the other provisions of the Act and of the purpose of the legislation ... such techniques cannot alter the result where the words of the statute are clear and plain and where the legal and practical effect of the transaction is undisputed&rdquo;.)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The OMDC's approach is unsustainable.</P>
<P>37. It flies in the face of the Digital Media Tax Credit's entire reason for existence: to create jobs in Ontario in the digital media industry.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 36 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 18]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong creates digital games that are entertaining. It employs dozens of people and expends significant resources in the development process. Pong's underlying motivation is, of course, to create profit by selling or licensing its games to third parties. That is the case with all for-profit entities.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 40 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 18]:
<QUOTE><P>The respondent submitted that the Ontario Media Development Corporation has a cultural aspect to it&mdash;a submission with which I agree. I recognize that the digital media tax credit is available to not-for-profit arts and cultural enterprises. I also recognize that those corporations do not have a profit motive. I do not believe this makes any difference to the proper interpretation of the regulation. The tax credit was introduced to benefit or assist the development of the interactive digital media industry. At the same time tax credits were introduced to benefit sound recording, computer animation and special effects companies and thereby create jobs in Ontario. The inclusion of not-for-profit arts and cultural enterprises was not accompanied by a corresponding restriction on the availability of this credit to for-profit corporations.</P></QUOTE></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong's games are attractive to third parties <BOLD><EM>because they entertain</EM></BOLD> and therefore offer an effective vehicle for the promotion of their products.</P>
<P>38. Furthermore, in licensing its games to third parties, Pong is also complying with a <EM>pre-requisite</EM> for eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit as set out in the OMDC's Guidelines&mdash;namely, that the product have a revenue generating stream. The Guidelines explicitly indicate that revenue generating streams may include licensing fees for use of the product and third party advertising within the product, which may come from promotion of the third party and/or the third party's products. In fact, without a revenue generating stream, the OMDC has indicated that it will consider the product to be primarily promotional. The OMDC cannot reasonably mandate that the product have a revenue generating stream and then punish the applicant for marketing its product in a way that derives revenue.</P>
<P>39. The OMDC's interpretation would create the perverse situation where digital gaming companies are forced to choose between licensing opportunities and eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit. That approach would actually <EM>discourage</EM> investment in the digital media field. Such an interpretation would defeat the purpose behind the Digital Media Tax Credit and is absurd. It is, therefore, unreasonable.</P>
<P>40. Indeed, as Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O. noted for the majority of the Divisional Court, it is nonsensical to cite the developer's profit-making motive as a reason for disqualifying it from the tax credit:
<QUOTE><P>A developer intending to license games will primarily want the games to promote the product of the licensee otherwise the licensee will not want the games. The respondent's reliance on this motivation or statements of it to conclude that the developer's product is primarily promotional and therefore not eligible for the tax credit means that the developer's fundamental purpose weighs negatively against eligibility for the tax credit, even though the legislature intended to use the tax credit to assist high-technology, knowledge-based industries.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 35 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 17]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>41. Thus, in denying Pong's application for the Digital Media Tax Credit, the OMDC conflated Pong's <EM>business model</EM> with its <EM>products' purpose</EM>. Pong develops its games to be entertaining to the user. Once developed, however, Pong must sell or license the games in order to derive revenue from them. Without revenue, it cannot create jobs.</P>
<P>42. The OMDC claims that the Divisional Court erred by focusing on the user's purpose for playing the games instead of the developer's purpose for developing the games. It says the user's purpose is less important because it &ldquo;will always be subjective&rdquo; and therefore difficult to pin down; the developer's purpose, in contrast, is discernable through, for example, the developer's promotional materials.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Appellant's Factum, at para. 60</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This does not make sense, and in any event does not come close to what the section actually says.</P>
<P>43. The user's purpose for playing Pong's digital games is not nebulous. It is obvious: users play the games to be entertained. Users do not play the games for their promotional content; the promotional content is placed in the game by a third party seeking to take advantage of the user's captivated attention.</P>
<P>44. Every developer's motivation is fixed: it is to derive revenue from the games. That is why the Regulations' language focuses on the user, not the developer. Focusing on the developer would mean that only not-for-profit product development would qualify for the credit. But that would render the Digital Media Tax Credit virtually unobtainable (because of the requirement of revenue).</P>
<P>45. The OMDC contends that under the Divisional Court's interpretation of the provision &ldquo;all interactive digital media products, and in particular all digital interactive games, regardless of their predominant purpose, would qualify.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellant's Factum, at para. 62</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This concern is without merit and easily dismissed. There is a litany of digital media products that would not be eligible for the tax credit because their primary purpose while being operated is not to &ldquo;educate, inform, or entertain&rdquo; the user. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Venngo inc. v. Ontario Media Development Corp.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Divisional Court upheld the OMDC's ruling that a coupon website did not qualify for the Digital Media Tax Credit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>[2013] O.J. No. 961 (Div. Ct) [OMDC's Book of Authorities (&ldquo;OMDC's BOA&rdquo;), at Tab 5]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Nor would every digital game qualify. The legislature has placed express limits on eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit by, for example, excluding products that promote the applicant's <EM>own</EM> products or services.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See s. 34(3) of the Regulations, <EM>supra</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> And, most significantly, as the Divisional Court pointed out, <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;[i]f the [OMDC] thinks that the regulation, properly interpreted, is not achieving the intended objective or is overly generous, then it is open to the Government to amend the regulation</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 39 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 18] (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. The government has, in fact, recently amended the Regulations and narrowed eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit. That is within its prerogative. It is <EM>not</EM>, however, open to the Appellant to ask the Court to retroactively read in limitations that did not exist at the relevant time.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>In-game promotional content is Irrelevant</EM></TI>
<P>47. Although nearly all of the OMDC's arguments are rehashed from its position in the court below, the OMDC has inserted a new argument in an attempt to fit itself within the Divisional Court's reasoning. At paragraphs 66 to 69 of its factum, the OMDC notes that the majority of the Divisional Court concluded that it was an error for the OMDC to focus its inquiry on the motivation of the game's developer rather than its user. The OMDC then asserts that it actually <EM>did</EM> focus on the user (at least in part) because, in concluding that the Gaming Products were primarily promotional, one of the things cited by the OMDC was promotional content that pops up when the Gaming Products are being played.</P>
<P>48. This argument completely misses the point of the Divisional Court's ruling (indeed, it reveals a flawed misunderstanding of what is at issue on this appeal). It is of course not in dispute that the Gaming Products have embedded promotional content that reaches the user during game play. If the promotional content contained in the Gaming Products didn't actually reach the user, the games wouldn't be very effective vehicles of promotion. Nor is it in dispute that the OMDC considered this promotional content.</P>
<P>49. But this assertion has no bearing on the central question here: whether it was unreasonable for the OMDC to disqualify Pong from receiving the Digital Medial Tax Credit solely because the Gaming Products are promotional, and despite the fact that the user obviously plays the game to be entertained. For the reasons submitted above, it was.</P>
<P>50. The OMDC's argument also contradicts its Guidelines. As noted above, examples of revenue generating streams, <EM>which are mandated by the OMDC</EM>, include <EM>&ldquo;[t]hird party advertising within the product&rdquo;</EM> and <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;in-game purchases&rdquo;</EM>.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Amended Guidelines, at p. 14 [Pong's Compendium, at Tab 4, p. 114] (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The OMDC cannot run from its own Guidelines.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>The Divisional Court Applied the Appropriate Standard of Review</TI>
<P>51. The Appellant argues that &ldquo;the majority effectively applied a standard of correctness and failed to grant the OMDC's decision the deference to which it is entitled.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellant's factum, at para 42</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This contention is groundless.</P>
<P>52. It is odd that Pong, the applicant in this matter, is put in the position of asserting that a reasonableness standard of review is appropriate here. In any event, Pong agrees that it is, and the Divisional Court rightly concluded as such. Quoting from <EM>Venngo</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, the Court found that the interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulations is &ldquo;a question that concerns OMDC's interpretation of its home legislation and is exactly the type of issue that falls within the OMDC's specialized expertise. The question ... lies at the core of the OMDC's function.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's reasons at para. 24 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, pp. 15-16], quoting <EM>Venngo</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 1</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. The problem with the OMDC's position is not that the Divisional Court failed to grant it deference. The problem with the OMDC's position is that its reading of s. 34(1) is unreasonable. Deference does not mean a body like the OMDC is a law unto itself. It remains subject to review. In approaching the OMDC's decision the Divisional Court cited <CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v. Ryan</SOC></CASEREF>, which states that &ldquo;an unreasonable decision [i]s one that did not stand up to a somewhat probing analysis.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2003 SCC 20, at para. 25 (see also at para. 47) [OMDC's BOA, at Tab 8], cited in Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 25 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 16]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Court conducted such an analysis and rightly concluded that the OMDC's decision could not withstand somewhat probing scrutiny.</P>
<P>54. A reasonableness standard accords deference to an administrative body's decisions where the application of the usual rules of statutory interpretation leave some ambiguity. It is important not to allow &ldquo;reasonableness&rdquo; to effectively <EM>immunize</EM> all decisions made by that administrative body. Here, the Divisional Court applied the correct standard of review and found that the OMDC's application of the Regulations in these circumstances was unreasonable. There is no basis to interfere with that finding.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>Even if the OMDC's Interpretation Was Reasonable, the Residual Assumption Applies</TI>
<P>55. The Appellant argues that the majority of the Divisional Court &ldquo;misapplied the residual presumption to the circumstances of this case.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellants Factum, at para. 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This assertion is also baseless.</P>
<P>56. Reasonableness and deference are engaged when, after the application of all relevant principles of statutory interpretation, ambiguity remains. As Moldaver J. said for the court in <CASEREF><SOC>McLean v. British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>It will not always be the case that a particular provision permits multiple reasonable interpretations. Where the ordinary tools of statutory interpretation lead to a single reasonable interpretation and the administrative decision maker adopts a different interpretation, its interpretation will necessarily be unreasonable&mdash;no degree of deference can justify its acceptance... In those cases, the &ldquo;range of reasonable outcomes&rdquo; <CASEREF><SOC>(Canada (Citizenship and Immigration) v. Khosa</SOC></CASEREF>, [...]) will necessarily be limited to a single reasonable interpretation&mdash;and the administrative decision maker must adopt it. [citations omitted].<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>McLean v. British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] S.C.J. No. 67</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Pong's BOA, at Tab 2]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>57. The residual presumption is an applicable principle that requires that &ldquo;a reasonable doubt, not resolved by the ordinary rules of interpretation,&rdquo; regarding the applicability of a tax credit &ldquo;will be settled by recourse to [a] residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>. para. 43, quoting <CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v. Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon-Secours</SOC><CITE>[1994] 3 S.C.R. 3</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF> [OMDC's BOA, at Tab 17]; see also <CASEREF><SOC>Valente v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2006] T.C.J. No. 92</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Pong's BOAr at Tab 3]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. As a preliminary matter, the Divisional Court did not <EM>apply</EM> the residual presumption. It therefore could not have misapplied it. The majority's reasons were very clear that it was <EM>not</EM> resorting to the residual presumption, due to its conclusion that the OMDC's decision was unreasonable. Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O. was unambiguous on this point; as he wrote: &ldquo;I do not find it necessary to resort to this principle to resolve this application because I do not think the respondent's interpretation is a reasonable one.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons at para. 43 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, pp. 18-19]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>59. In any event, the parties are essentially <EM>ad idem</EM> on the applicability of the residual presumption. The OMDC writes that &ldquo;[w]hen there are two interpretations and one cannot be said to be the more reasonable than the other, <EM>the choice should then be resolved in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo;</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellant's Factum, at para. 73 (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong agrees with this statement and so would Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O.</P>
<P>60. The OMDC's position <EM>at its highest</EM> is that Its interpretation is <EM>equally</EM> reasonable. Surely, in light of the plain wording of s. 34(1), it cannot be said that the OMDC's reading is <EM>more</EM> reasonable than Pong's. Accordingly, the OMDC apparently concedes that the residual presumption should apply here.</P>
<P>61. Despite this apparent admission, the OMDC proceeds to argue that the residual presumption should not apply because &ldquo;[i]f the OMDC's decision is reasonable, then by definition there is no ambiguity in the interpretation of the legislation requiring resort to the residual presumption; it is necessarily implied that no unresolvable dispute exists regarding the meaning of the provision.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellant's Factum at para. 81</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>62. This reasoning is tautological and unhelpful (it also contradicts the OMDC's earlier concession that the residual presumption should apply where there are two equally reasonable interpretations). The OMDC's claim is essentially that we know the residual presumption does not apply because the OMDC didn't apply it. In the court below, Justice Sachs said essentially the same thing:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 88 [AB&amp;C, at Tab 3, p. 27] (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P><CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v. Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon-Secours</SOC><CITE>[1994] 3 S.C.R. 3</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>171 N.R. 161</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> and the cases that have followed it have made it clear that the presumption at issue now has a very limited role to play in the interpretation of tax legislation, it is a residual presumption that should only be resorted to if it is not possible to resolve the meaning of the legislation by applying. Driedger's modern approach to statutory interpretation. <UNDER>In this case, the OMDC was able to resolve the meaning of the legislation in question without resort to the residual presumption</UNDER>. A reasonableness review requires that the OMDC's decision in this regard be respected unless it falls outside the range of possible and acceptable outcomes.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>63. With great respect for Justice Sachs, this logic cannot be right. In all cases, the administrative body will reach a decision. The mere fact that the decision maker reached a decision tells you nothing in and of itself about the reasonableness of that decision. Moreover, if Justice Sachs is correct that the residual presumption does not apply here because the OMDC &ldquo;resolv[ed] the meaning of the legislation in question&rdquo; without applying it, then the residual presumption would apply only at the whim of the administrative body. That is nonsensical and risks eliminating the residual presumption entirely.</P>
<P>64. Furthermore, there are important policy reasons for why the residual presumption is warranted in precisely this type of case.</P>
<P>65. As seen above in the discussion regarding similarly-situated companies like Fuel, the OMDC has granted the Digital Medial Tax Credit to companies whose business models are virtually indistinguishable from Fong's. Indeed, there is no appreciable difference between Pong's desire to &ldquo;create consumer involvement with a brand or product and thus encourage consumption of that product&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated July 29, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 711]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and Fuel's goal of &ldquo;help[ing] Fortune 500 global brands connect with GenZ, Millennial and Family audiences using deep, digital brand experiences&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through OAP between W. Dawson and M. Olivier dated July 29, 2015 [OMDC's EB, at Tab 9, p. 711]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Moreover, Fuel's games are chock-full of in-game promotional content aimed at the user.</P>
<P>66. It is a fundamental principle of the interpretation of taxation statutes that like taxpayers should be treated alike.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g., <CASEREF><SOC>Jonas v. Gilbert</SOC><CITE>[1881] S.C.J. No. 5</CITE><PAGENUM>at pp. 6 and 7</PAGENUM></CASEREF> [Pong's BOA, Tab 4]; <CASEREF><SOC>65302 British Columbia Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[1999] 3 S.C.R. 804</CITE><PARANUM>60</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Pong's BOA, at Tab 5]; <CASEREF><SOC>McNeil v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2000] 4 F.C. 132</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 14 [Pong's BOA, at Tab 6]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It is unfair and irrational to apply a tax benefit in two different ways to identical companies, even if it could be said that both interpretations of the relevant provision are reasonable. This creates an uneven playing field.</P>
<P>67. It also a fundamental principle of the interpretation of taxation statutes that taxes should be applied in a predictable manner. As explained by the Federal Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Gunn v. Canada</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>[S]tatutory interpretation must be informed by the recognition that, in a self-assessing tax system that respects the right of taxpayers to plan their tax affairs intelligently, taxpayers require rules that are consistent, predictable and fair. These objectives are undermined by provisions that are so vague that their application cannot be predicted with reasonable certainty. <UNDER>They may be further undermined if they are applied on the basis of a judge-made rule that has no statutory foundation</UNDER>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gunn v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2007] 3 F.C.R. 57</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 78 [Pong's BOA, Tab 7], citing <CASEREF><SOC>Canada Trustco Mortgage Co. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2005] 2 S.C.R. 601</CITE></CASEREF> [Pong's BOA, Tab 8] (emphasis added and Internal citation omitted)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Certainty is particularly vital in this context because companies like Pong must decide <EM>before</EM> they manufacture their products what their expenses will be. Recall that the Digital Media Tax Credit represents up to <BOLD><EM>40%</EM></BOLD> of a company's labour, marketing, and distribution costs. Needless to say, this is a significant portion of a company's balance sheet.</P>
<P>68. Without consistency and predictability the Digital Media Tax Credit cannot fulfill its purpose: to encourage investment in Ontario's digital media industry. Uncertainty and unpredictability frustrates investment. Companies like Pong must be made to feel secure that if they comply with the plain language of eligibility for the credit they will be entitled to it. Otherwise, they will not take the risk of spending millions of dollars that they may never get back (or borrowing millions of dollars they may never be able to repay). In addition, companies will not hire additional employees if they are uncertain as to whether they will have the resources to pay for them.</P>
<P>69. Accordingly although the question of the applicability of the residual presumption in this case is a purely academic one, it is clear that the residual presumption exists for this <EM>precise</EM> set of circumstances and should apply.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ADDITIONAL ISSUES</TI>
<P>70. The Respondent raises no additional issues.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>71. The Respondent respectfully requests:
<P1>(a) An order dismissing this appeal and affirming the ruling of the Divisional Court;</P1>
