<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF MOTION</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE MOVING PARTY,</BOLD> the Ontario Media Development Corporation (&ldquo;OMDC&rdquo;), will make a motion to the Court of Appeal for leave to appeal from the Judgment of the Divisional Court, <EM>per</EM> Associate Chief Justice Marrocco, and Justices Nordheimer and Sachs, made January 25, 2017.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE COURT WILL HEAR THE MOTION IN WRITING,</BOLD> 36 days after service of the Moving Party's Motion Record, Factum and transcripts, if any, or on the filing of the Moving Party's Reply Factum, if any, whichever is earlier.</P>
<P>The motion will be heard at Osgoode Hall, Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P><BOLD>PROPOSED METHOD OF HEARING:</BOLD> The motion is to be heard in writing.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE MOTION IS FOR:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. An order granting leave to appeal from the Judgment;</P>
<P>2. The costs of this motion; and</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THE MOTION ARE:</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit</EM></TI>
<P>1. The OMDC is an agency of the Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Sport. It was established to promote innovation, investment and employment in Ontario's cultural media industry, and to administer tax credit programs in furtherance of that objective.</P>
<P>2. The Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit (&ldquo;OIDMTC&rdquo;) is a refundable tax credit for the development of eligible interactive digital media products in Ontario. If a product is eligible for the OIDMTC, the applicant corporation may claim a percentage of Ontario labour expenditures, and certain marketing and distribution expenditures incurred during the product's development.</P>
<P>3. Pursuant to section 93 of the <EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, the OMDC is responsible for determining whether a corporation is eligible for the OIDMTC, and whether a product is an eligible product for the OIDMTC.</P>
<P>4. Section 34(1) of O Reg 37/09, made under the <EM>Taxation Act 2007</EM>, specifies that an eligible product must be an &ldquo;interactive digital media product.&rdquo; Among other requirements, in order to qualify as an interactive digital media product, the primary purpose of the product must be to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user.&rdquo; Products that are determined by the OMDC to be primarily promotional in nature do not qualify for the tax credit.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Pong Marketing and Development Inc.'s Application for the OIDMTC</EM></TI>
<P>5. In April 2014, Pong Marketing and Development Inc. applied for the OIDMTC with respect to 15 casino-style sweepstakes game products. These products were developed to be licenced to third party retailers, as part of a promotional program. Following its review of the products and information provided by Pong Marketing, the OMDC determined that the 15 products did not satisfy the eligibility requirements set out in section 34(1), because their primary purpose was not to educate, inform, or entertain the user. Rather, the OMDC determined that the primary purpose of the products was to promote the sale of phone cards and other related products and services.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Judicial Review of the OMDC Decision</EM></TI>
<P>6. Pong Marketing sought judicial review of the OMDC decision that the 15 products were ineligible. Pong Marketing argued that the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) was unreasonable, and that the OMDC had failed to provide sufficient reasons for the decision.</P>
<P>7. The Divisional Court released a split decision on January 25, 2017, granting the application.</P>
<P>8. In its decision, the majority allowed the application, finding that the OMDC's interpretation of section 34(1) was unreasonable, holding that the only reasonable interpretation of section 34(1) &ldquo;requires the OMDC to look at the primary purpose of the game from the perspective of the player.&rdquo; The majority concluded that the OMDC had unreasonably considered the purpose for which the product was developed, which it held was an irrelevant consideration.</P>
<P>9. In addition, the majority held that even if the OMDC interpretation of section 34(1) was reasonable, a residual presumption that operates in favour of the taxpayer should be applied in the interpretation of taxation statutes. The majority held that this presumption should have been applied by the OMDC in this case.</P>
<P>10. Finally, the majority rejected Pong Marketing's argument that the reasons provided by the OMDC were insufficient.</P>
<P>11. The dissenting judge would have dismissed the application on the basis that deference should be afforded to the OMDC in its interpretation of the eligibility criteria under section 34(1). The dissent concluded that it was reasonable for the OMDC to consider the intended purpose of the product at the time of its creation when attempting to determine the primary purpose of the product while being operated. Accordingly, the OMDC's determination that the primary purpose of the games was to promote the sale of phone cards based on, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the purpose for which the products was developed, was entitled to deference.</P>
<P>12. Further, the dissenting judge noted that the residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer has a limited purpose, and is only applied if it is not possible to resolve the meaning of the legislation using the modern approach to statutory interpretation. In this case, the residual presumption has no application as the OMDC was able to resolve the issue without needing to resort to the residual presumption.</P>
<P>13. The dissenting judge agreed with the majority that the OMDC's reasons were sufficient.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Appeal Has Merit and Bakes Issues of Public Importance</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. The OMDC has strong grounds for appeal on the following issues:
<P1>a. The majority erred in failing to give any deference to the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute, and as such erroneously applied a standard of correctness;</P1>
<P1>b. The majority erred in holding that it was unreasonable for the OMDC to consider the purpose for which the products were developed when assessing whether the products' predominant purpose was promotional:</P1>
<P1>c. The majority erred in failing to give weight to the evidence showing that the OMDC did consider the promotional content of the products presented to users while in operation;</P1>
<P1>d. The majority erred in finding that the residual presumption in favour of taxpayers would have any application in this case, and that it would favour the respondent; and</P1>
<P1>e. The dissenting decision showed the appropriate deference to the OMDC's expertise and properly found that the OMDC's statutory interpretation and findings were reasonable.</P1></P>
<P>15. The appeal raises issues of public importance. The matters at issue on this appeal concern the interpretation of a statute and regulation of general application. The appeal also raises questions concerning the broader principles applicable to the interpretation of taxation statutes by administrative decision makers.</P>
<P>16. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION</BOLD> is section 6(1)(a) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> and rule 61.03.1 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
