<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDENT/MOVING PARTY, ONTARIO MEDIA DEVELOPMENT CORPORATION</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART 1&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Ontario Media Development Corporation (&ldquo;OMDC&rdquo;) seeks leave to appeal from the judgment of the Divisional Court, dated February 25, 2017. The Divisional Court granted the Respondent Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc.'s (&ldquo;Pong Marketing&rdquo;) application for judicial review of the OMDC's decision that 15 &ldquo;casino-style&rdquo; sweepstakes games are ineligible for the Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit (&ldquo;OIDMTC&rdquo;). Pong Marketing's OIDMTC application was remitted back to the OMDC for reconsideration.</P>
<P>2. The central issue on the proposed appeal is the interpretation of taxation legislation governing tax credits available to the rapidly evolving interactive digital media industry. If granted, this appeal engages significant issues of public importance, including the interpretation of a statute and regulation of general application, and broader questions concerning the principles applicable to the interpretation of taxation statutes by administrative decision makers.</P>
<P>3. The OMDC is an agency of Ontario's Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Sport, that was established to promote innovation, investment and employment in Ontario's cultural media industry, and to administer the OIDMTC in furtherance of that objective. To be eligible for the OIDMTC, a product's primary purpose must be to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user.&rdquo; Products that are primarily promotional do not meet the primary purpose test.</P>
<P>4. On its review of Pong Marketing's application, the OMDC found that the primary purpose of Pong Marketing's products is to promote the sale of long-distance calling cards, not to educate, inform or entertain the user. The OMDC's decision was based on a review of the 15 sweepstakes games themselves, as well as the materials submitted by Pong Marketing, including its template licensing agreements and website. In a split decision, the majority of the Divisional Court held that the OMDC's interpretation of O Reg 37/09 (the &ldquo;<EM>Regulation</EM>&rdquo;) under the <EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, S.O. 2007 c. 11 Sched A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (the &ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;), was unreasonable because it considered the intended purpose of the product when it was being developed. Instead, the majority found that the only reasonable interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> requires the purpose of the sweepstakes games to be assessed exclusively from the perspective of the user during gameplay. The majority further held that even if the OMDC's decision was reasonable, the residual presumption applicable to tax legislation would require resolving any ambiguity in the interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> in favour of the taxpayer.</P>
<P>5. The OMDC submits that the majority made significant errors of law in its decision. In particular, and as noted by the dissenting judge, the majority erred by:
<P1>(a) Misinterpreting s. 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM>. The majority's interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> is too narrow and reads in limitations to the scope of the provision that undermine the legislative intent;</P1>
<P1>(b) Failing to grant deference to the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute, and in doing so, erroneously applying a standard of correctness. It was reasonable for the ODMC to consider, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the intended purpose of the product at the time of its creation when assessing the primary purpose of the product. The ODMC's decision in this regard is entitled to deference; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Misapplying the residual presumption to the circumstances of this case. As noted by the dissenting judge, the residual presumption has a &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; role to play in the interpretation of tax legislation and should not apply in a case such as this one where the OMDC's interpretation is reasonable and is supported by the intent and wording of the legislative and regulatory scheme.</P1></P>
<P>6. It is both desirable and in the public interest for leave to be granted. The <EM>Act</EM> is a statute of general application and the interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> is an issue that extends beyond the interests of the immediate parties. The proper administration of tax credits in the cultural media sector affects thousands of individuals employed in the industry, and has a significant impact on a major source of revenue for the province.</P>
<P>7. Moreover, determining the appropriate degree of deference that should be afforded to administrative decision makers' interpretation of taxation statutes and the intersection between the reasonableness standard of review and the application of the residual presumption are also issues of general importance that extend beyond the parties to this litigation.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART 2&mdash;SUMMARY OF THE FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The OMDC and the OIDMTC</TI>
<P>8. The OMDC is an agency of the Ontario Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Sport. It was established in 2000 to promote innovation, investment and employment in Ontario's cultural media industry, and to administer tax credit programs in furtherance of that objective.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>O Reg 672/00, ss. 1, 2, 3, 4, <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. The OIDMTC is a refundable tax credit for the development of eligible interactive digital media products in Ontario. If a product is eligible for the OIDMTC, the applicant corporation may claim a percentage of its Ontario labour expenditures, and certain marketing and distribution expenditures incurred during the product's development. As a refundable tax credit, the amount of the credit, less any taxes payable, is paid to the corporation.</P>
<P>10. The OIDMTC is jointly administered by the OMDC and the Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;). Corporations can submit an application to the OMDC for a Certificate of Eligibility for a product, pursuant to s. 93 of the <EM>Act</EM>. The OMDC reviews the application, and if the product meets the legislative requirements, the OMDC will issue a Certificate of Eligibility certifying that a product is eligible for the OIDMTC. The corporation can then resubmit its certificate to the CRA, which conducts an audit and issues a refund in cases where the corporation is entitled to a refund.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, SO 2007 c 11 Sched A, s. 93 (8&ndash;10), <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Legislative Scheme</TI>
<P>11. Pong Marketing's OIDMTC application submitted to the OMDC is governed by s. 93 of <EM>the Act</EM>, and s. 34 of the <EM>Regulation</EM>.</P>
<P>12. Under s. 93 of the <EM>Act</EM>, the OMDC is responsible for determining whether a corporation is eligible for the OIDMTC, and whether a product is an eligible product for the OIDMTC.</P>
<P>13. A &ldquo;qualifying corporation&rdquo; must develop an eligible product to qualify for the OIDMTC. Eligible products are defined at s. 93(14) of the <EM>Act:</EM>
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(14)</N><SSECP>In this section,
<DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;eligible product&rdquo;</TERM> means, in respect of a qualifying corporation, a product,
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>that satisfies the prescribed conditions or that is a specified product, and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>for which public financial support would not be contrary to the public policy in the opinion of the Ontario Media Development Corporation or, if another person is designated for the purposes of subsection (8), in the opinion of that person;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Taxation Act, 2007</EM>, SO 2007 c 11 Sched A, s. 93(14), <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>14. Section 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM> specifies that an eligible product must be an &ldquo;interactive digital media product.&rdquo; Among other requirements, in order to qualify as an interactive digital media product, the primary purpose of the product must be to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>34.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In this section,
<DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo;</TERM> means a combination of one or more application files and one or more data files, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and that have the following characteristics when they are being operated:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>Their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user.</PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>O. Reg. 37/09, s. 34(1), <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Pong Marketing's Application and Game Content</TI>
<P>15. On April 16, 2014, Pong Marketing applied to the OMDC for the OIDMTC (&ldquo;the application&rdquo;). The application concerned 15 sweepstakes games (&ldquo;the sweepstakes games&rdquo;) that Pong Marketing developed between February 2011 and March 2013. The total tax credit being sought by Pong Marketing is approximately $2 million.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>Motion Record of the OMDC (&ldquo;OMDC MR&rdquo;), Tab 3, p 13, paras 3-4</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The sweepstakes games are &ldquo;casino-style&rdquo; slot-based games that work by sequentially delivering sweepstakes prizes to the player upon the commitment of &ldquo;sweepstakes points.&rdquo; A player receives sweepstakes points each time he or she purchases a telephone card. A player can also receive points by requesting entry into a game without making a purchase. While the outcome of the game is predetermined, the number of points affects a participant's chance of winning a prize.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 14, para 16</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. The games are intended to be licensed to third party retailers, including cafe owners, and owners of bars and restaurants, as part of a promotional program to generate revenue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Game Document, &ldquo;Amazing 8s&rdquo;, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 140</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The games are operated through a gaming platform that is licensed to retailers by Pong Marketing.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Marketing Document, &ldquo;Amazing 8s&rdquo;, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 140, 559.</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. Pong Marketing's marketing materials specifically promote their products as being responsive to the market's need for the commercialization of sweepstakes gaming products.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Marketing Document, &ldquo;Amazing 8s&rdquo;, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 140</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. Pong Marketing receives a percentage of revenue generated from the gameplay.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc., &ldquo;Business Model Clarification Final&rdquo;, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 559</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The OMDC Decision</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>The OMDC's Initial Review of Pong Marketing's Application</TI>
<P>20. The OMDC's initial review of Pong Marketing's development, licensing and marketing documents concluded that the sweepstakes games did not qualify for the OIDMTC because it appeared that the products' purpose was primarily promotional. In particular, the OMDC concluded that the sweepstakes games were produced for the primary purpose of selling long distance phone cards.</P>
<P>21. Pong Marketing's documents were assessed for key factors, including why and how a product was developed, what audience or target market it was developed for, and who the product was marketed to; this process included a review of Pong Marketing's template licensing agreement, website content, and screenshots of the sweepstakes games themselves.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from Jennifer Blitz to William Dawson, re &ldquo;OIDMTC Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. 2013 File No. 15214-01-TXM&rdquo; (November 30, 2015), <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 770</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. In arriving at its initial decision, the OMDC wrote to Pong Marketing and cited several examples from the application materials that demonstrated the sweepstakes games' primarily promotional purpose. Among them was explicit language in the template licensing agreement that defined the sweepstakes games as: &ldquo;A means of promotion to aid in the sale of long distance calling cards and other related products and services.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Template Licensing Agreement&mdash;&ldquo;Amazing 8s&rdquo;, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 234</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. Additionally, the template licensing agreement provided, in part, that:
<P1>(a) The licensor (i.e., Pong Marketing) is in the business of providing a &ldquo;delivery system&rdquo; that includes loyalty platform software, wholesale telephone communication delivery services, internet time, a database, operational hardware and operational software;</P1>
<P1>(b) The licensor's operational hardware includes the computer terminals on which the game is played;</P1>
<P1>(c) The licensee is in the business of selling long-distance calling cards, office services and related retail products and desires to use the applicant's delivery system in all its business locations;</P1>
<P1>(d) Gross profit, on which the licensing fees are based, is the money received from the purchase of long-distance phone time less the amount paid out in prizes; and</P1>
<P1>(e) The licensee is required to pay to the licensor 15 percent of the gross profit from each of the licensee's business locations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 14, para 20;</BOLD> Template Licensing Agreement&mdash;&ldquo;Amazing 8s&rdquo;, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 234</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>24. Similar language found on Pong Marketing's website described their business model as a method by which to promote telephone cards:
<P1>(a) Pong Marketing is a Telecommunication Company in the business of delivering a promotional sweepstakes system to enhance the sale of its pre-paid long distance phone time;</P1>
<P1>(b) In order to compete against the industries [sic] top competitors in the phone card market...Pong Marketing has introduced a promotional program that includes Sweepstakes games;</P1>
<P1>(c) The idea of sweepstakes is to create consumer involvement with a brand or product and thus encourage consumption of the product;</P1>
<P1>(d) The adoption of interactive video game promotions continues at an extraordinary rate, with more marketers embracing this delivery system for sweepstakes giveaways.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 15, para 23;</BOLD> Correspondence through the Online Application Portal (&ldquo;OAP&rdquo;) from OMDC to Pong Marketing, July 29, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 754</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>25. The OMDC explained to Pong Marketing that to be eligible for the tax credit, the purpose of the product must be primarily to educate, inform or entertain the user. Products deemed to be primarily promotional do not qualify. The OMDC offered Pong Marketing the opportunity to file additional documentation that might address the OMDC's concern that the purpose of the sweepstakes games is primarily promotional.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>Further Documentation Provided by Pong Marketing</TI>
<P>26. In response to the OMDC's concerns, Pong Marketing submitted additional documentation, including a document entitled &ldquo;business model clarification.&rdquo; The OMDC reviewed the business clarification model, and advised Pong Marketing that it did not address the concerns that the OMDC had raised.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence though the OAP from Pong Marketing to OMDC, September 8, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 762;</BOLD> Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc., &ldquo;Business Model Clarification Final,&rdquo; <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 559-560</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. Pong Marketing subsequently filed further supporting documentation for review, which included:
<P1>(a) Game videos from each of the 15 sweepstake-games;</P1>
<P1>(b) Pictures from internet cafes where the games were being played;</P1>
<P1>(c) Marketing and game revenue materials;</P1>
<P1>(d) A YouTube demonstration video; and</P1>
<P1>(e) Screen shots from a &ldquo;Pong Studios&rdquo; website.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Supplementary Application Materials, filed by Pong Marketing on Sept. 24, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, p 561&ndash;740</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>28. The game videos provided as part of the supplementary documents allowed the OMDC the opportunity to view the content embedded in each of the sweepstakes games from the perspective of the user during gameplay. Additional items, such as photos of the venues where the games are operated, and the demonstration video that may be viewed by users, provided additional insight into the products' use from the user's perspective.</P>
<P>29. Upon reviewing these materials, the OMDC wrote to Pong Marketing on October 23, 2015, and advised that their decision regarding the primarily promotional purpose of the sweepstakes games remained unchanged.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through the OAP from the OMDC to Pong Marketing, Oct. 23, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 757&ndash;761</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As part of its reasons, the OMDC cited the prominent in-game promotional content in each of the 15 sweepstakes games that confronted users during gameplay.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through the OAP from the OMDC to Pong Marketing, Oct. 23, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 757&ndash;759</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. In the same correspondence of October 23<SUP>rd</SUP>, the OMDC explained why it also did not find the additional items persuasive. The reasons provided by the OMDC include the following:
<P1>(a) Some of the internet caf&ea; pictures contained long distance phone card signs;</P1>
<P1>(b) Most of the marketing material submitted was not related to the sweepstakes games at issue on the OIDMTC application;</P1>
<P1>(c) The YouTube video contained an animated character that congratulates the user on purchasing a phone card;</P1>
<P1>(d) The website screenshots submitted did not match the licensing agreements submitted with the sweepstakes games.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through the OAP from the OMDC to Pong Marketing. October 23, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 759&ndash;761</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>iii.</N><TI>The OMDC's Finding that the Primary Purpose of the Sweepstakes Games is Promotional</TI>
<P>31. At Pong Marketing's request, the OMDC reviewed the application again. That review was conducted by the assigned case officer, the OIDMTC Team Leader, and the OMDC Director of Tax Credits and Financing. At the conclusion of this review, the OMDC determined that the primary purpose of the sweepstakes games is promotional.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from OMDC to Pong Marketing, re &ldquo;OIDMTC Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. 2013 File No. 15214-01-TXM&rdquo; (November 30, 2015) <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 770&ndash;775</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. The OMDC issued a formal letter of ineligibility on December 11, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from OMDC to Pong Marketing, re &ldquo;OIDMTC Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. [...]&rdquo; (December 11, 2015), <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 5, p 37</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>The Divisional Court Decision</TI>
<P>33. The majority of the Divisional Court allowed Pong Marketing's application and remitted the matter back to the OMDC for reconsideration. Writing for the majority, Associate Chief Justice Marrocco (Nordheimer J., concurring) found that the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM> was unreasonable. The majority held that the only reasonable interpretation of s. 34(1) requires the ODMC to look at &ldquo;the primary purpose of the game from the perspective of the player&rdquo; because the section refers to the &ldquo;characteristics of the game when the user is playing it.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 19, para 38</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>34. Moreover, as the wording of s. 34(1) makes no mention of the developer, the majority held that any consideration of the developer's motivation for developing the game is irrelevant to the OMDC's assessment of whether the purpose of the games, while in operation, is primarily promotional. This reasoning flows from the majority's literal reading of the definition of &ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo; under the <EM>Regulation</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>The definition focuses on the time when the application files and data files are operated together by the user <BOLD><EM>and provides that one of their characteristics at that moment is that their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user</EM>.</BOLD> The only time the user <BOLD><EM>operates</EM></BOLD> those files is when he or she is playing a Sweepstakes game. The primary purpose of the applicant when creating or licensing the product is a different inquiry.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 18, paras 32-33</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis original]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>35. Accordingly, the majority regarded any statements from Pong Marketing's website or template licensing agreement used as a means of indicating the developer's intention when developing the sweepstakes games to be unhelpful in determining the primary purpose of the product when it is being operated.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, pp 18-19, paras 37-38</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. The majority further held that even if the OMDC's interpretation of s. 34(1) is reasonable, a residual presumption that applies in favour of the taxpayer in the interpretation of taxation statutes should have been applied, by the OMDC in this case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 19, para 43</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. By contrast, in her dissenting reasons, Justice Sachs would have denied the application. Contrary to the approach taken by the majority, the dissent held that the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute warranted deference. Her Honour held that a reasonable interpretation of the legislation does not preclude the OMDC from considering the purpose for which the product is developed in determining the product's purpose:
<QUOTE><P>[...] it is not unreasonable when objectively assessing the primary purpose of a product while it is being operated to have regard to what the intended purpose of the product was when it was being developed. After all, it is the product's primary purpose that governs the analysis and it is reasonable to assume that a successfully developed product, when it is being operated, will fulfill the primary purpose for which it was developed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 27, para 84</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>38. Further, the dissent noted that the legislation specifically contemplates that an eligible product may have multiple purposes while it is being operated by the user. As such, it is the OMDC's statutory responsibility to determine the primary purpose of the product. In this case, the dissent noted that the OMDC is entitled to rely on its review of the sweepstakes games, among other things, to find that the primary purpose of the products while they are being operated is to encourage users to buy calling cards, and not to entertain.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 27, para 85</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. As for the residual presumption, the dissent found that the residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer serves a &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; purpose, and is only applied if it is not possible to resolve the meaning of the legislation using the modem approach to statutory interpretation. In this case, Sachs J. held that the residual presumption has no application as the OMDC resolved the issue without needing to resort to the residual presumption.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 28, paras 87-88</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART 3&mdash;THE ISSUES</TI>
<P>40. If leave is granted, the OMDC proposes the following questions on appeal:
<P1>(a) Did the Divisional Court err by misinterpreting s. 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM> such that the scope of the provision is unnecessarily limited?</P1>
<P1>(b) Did the Divisional Court err in failing to give any deference to the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute, and as such erroneously apply a standard of correctness?</P1>
<P1>(c) Did the Divisional Court err in finding that the residual presumption in favour of taxpayers would have any application in this case and that it would favour the respondent?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART 4&mdash;THE LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>The Test for Leave to Appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>41. Rule 61.03.1 provides that a motion for leave to appeal to the Court of Appeal is to be brought in writing. As set out in the case law, matters to be considered in granting leave include: (a) whether the appeal involves the interpretation of a statute or regulation including its constitutionality; (b) the interpretation, clarification or propounding of some general rule or principle of law; and (c) whether the interpretation of the law or agreement in issue is of significance only to the parties or whether a question of general interest to the public or a broad segment of the public would be settled for the future.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Re Sault Dock Co. Ltd. and Pity of Sault Ste. Marie</SOC><CITE>[1973] 2 OR 479</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Book of Authorities of the OMDC (&ldquo;OMDC BOA&rdquo;), Tab 1</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. As set out below, the OMDC submits that there is substantial merit to the three proposed issues for appeal. The proposed appeal also raises issues of public importance which are addressed in the last section of the factum.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>The Majority Erred in their Interpretation of s. 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>43. The majority erred by interpreting s. 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM> as prohibiting a consideration of the purpose for which the products were developed.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>The Rules of Statutory Interpretation</TI>
<P>44. The Supreme Court of Canada has repeatedly endorsed Driedger's modem approach to statutory interpretation:
<QUOTE><P>[T]he words of an <EM>Act</EM> are to be read in their entire context and in their grammatical and ordinary sense harmoniously with the scheme of the <EM>Act</EM>, the object of the <EM>Act</EM>, and the intention of Parliament.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Elmer A. Driedger, <EM>Construction of Statutes</EM>, 2nd ed. (Toronto: Butterworths, 1983) at 87, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 2;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership v Rex</SOC><CITE>[2002] SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 3;</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>45. The modern approach to statutory interpretation requires the court to: (i) examine the words of the provision in their ordinary and grammatical sense; (ii) consider the entire context that the provision is located within; and (iii) consider whether the proposed interpretation produces a just and reasonable result.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership v Rex</SOC><CITE>[2002] SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 3;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bapoo v Cooperators General Insurance Co</SOC><CITE>[1997] OJ No 5055</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><PARANUM>8</PARANUM><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 4</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. The factors comprising the &ldquo;entire context&rdquo; include the history of the provision at issue, its place in the overall scheme of the Act, the object of the Act itself, and the Legislature's intent in enacting the Act as a whole and the particular provision at issue. A just and reasonable result promotes applications of the Act that advance its purpose and avoids applications that are &ldquo;foolish and pointless.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pierre-Andr&ea; C&oc;t&ea;, <EM>The Interpretation of Legislation in Canada</EM>, 3rd ed. (Scarborough: Thomson Canada Limited, 2000) at p 387, <BOLD>OMDC BOA Tab 5</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>The Majority's Interpretation of s. 34(1) is Too Narrow</TI>
<P>47. Section 34(1) of the <EM>Regulation</EM> reads as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>34.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In this section,
<DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo;</TERM> means a combination of one or more application files and one or more data files, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and that have the following characteristics <UNDER>when they are being operated</UNDER>:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP><UNDER>Their</UNDER> primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>O. Reg. 37/09, s. 34(1), <BOLD>Schedule B</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>48. For the majority, the central concern with interpreting s. 34(1) as allowing a consideration of the developer's purpose, as favoured by the OMDC, is that the &ldquo;developer's fundamental purpose&rdquo; may weigh negatively against their eligibility for the tax credit. This, they held, is inconsistent with the Legislature's intention to use the tax credit to assist high technology, knowledge-based industries.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 18, para 35</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>49. Accordingly, the majority interpreted s. 34(1) as avoiding this problem by focusing on the characteristics of the product from the subjective perspective of the user while the user plays the game.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 18, para 37</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Respectfully, this interpretation is too narrow.</P>
<P>50. When read in its entire context and in the grammatical and ordinary sense, s. 34(1) does not prohibit consideration of the purpose for which a product was developed. It is evident on a plain reading of s. 34(1) that this provision can be interpreted to include the purpose for which the product was developed. The reference to &ldquo;they&rdquo; in &ldquo;when <UNDER>they</UNDER> are being operated ... <UNDER>Their</UNDER> primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo;, is a reference to the product's purpose and not the user's purpose. The user's purpose will always be subjective. Users may play games to be entertained or to benefit from the products the games promote, or both. But the developer's purpose in developing the products can be ascertained from the games and promotional materials, and is necessarily relevant to determining the game's overall purpose while they are being operated.</P>
<P>51. Focus on the purpose for which the games were developed is more consistent with the purpose for which the OIDMTC is made available. Contrary to the majority's premise, and as correctly identified in the dissent, the tax credit is intended to facilitate growth in the cultural media sector and not the interactive digital media industry writ large.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 26, para 77</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The determination as to whether a product is eligible for the OIDMTC is a task that has been delegated to the OMDC. The OMDC's mandate is to &ldquo;foster the development and enhancement of the cultural media industry in Ontario.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 26, para 77</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This mandate is not, however, intended to create jobs generally in the digital media industry, but rather to &ldquo;create jobs in particular sectors&rdquo; of that industry.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 26, para 77</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. For this reason the <EM>Regulation</EM> requires an assessment of the product's primary purpose to ensure that it is intended to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user.&rdquo; If the intention was simply to create jobs through a broadly administered tax credit, then all interactive digital media products, and in particular all digital interactive games, regardless of their predominant purpose, would qualify. This is not what the Legislature intended.</P>
<P>53. Viewed in this way, there is a logical link between a product developer's intention and the end product's operation. As Sachs J. stated, it is &ldquo;reasonable to assume that a product when operated successfully will fulfill the primary purpose for which it was developed.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 27, para 84</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> When the primary purpose of a product is the focal point for determining eligibility for a tax credit, it is reasonable to refer to the developer's intention as the OMDC did in this case.</P>
<P>54. Accordingly, by focusing on the subjective purpose for which a user may play one of the sweepstakes games, the majority interpreted s. 34(1) too narrowly, and without reference to the wording of the provision as a whole and the purpose of the OIDMTC. In addition, as set out below, the majority failed to accord the deference owed to the OMDC in interpreting its own statute.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>The Majority Erred by Failing to Grant the OMDC's Decision Any Deference</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. The majority's decision misapplies the reasonableness standard of review to the OMDC's decision. Rather than assessing the OMDC's decision against the principles of justification, transparency and intelligibility, the majority substituted its own interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> for that of the OMDC. As such, the majority arguably applied a standard of correctness and failed to grant the OMDC's decision the deference to which it is entitled.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>Deference should be afforded on a Reasonableness Standard of Review</TI>
<P>56. The Court correctly held that the standard of review of the OMDC's decision in this case is reasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 16, para 24</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>57. Under the reasonableness standard of review, deference is the animating principle.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Dummuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>47</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 6</BOLD> (excerpt); <CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] 3 SCR 895</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 7</BOLD> (excerpt)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The OMDC's decision can only be considered unreasonable if &ldquo;there is no line of analysis within the given reasons that could reasonably lead the [OMDC] from the evidence before it to the conclusion at which it arrived.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 20</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 8</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The OMDC's decision may be reasonable even if its explanation is not one that the reviewing court finds compelling.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 20</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 8</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. It is a &ldquo;grave misconception&rdquo; for the Court to determine the reasonableness of the OMDC's decision by examining whether its decision &ldquo;deviates from the correct decision by more than a reasonable margin of error...&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Abdoulrab v Ontario (Labour Relations Board)</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 491</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 9</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No single outcome can be regarded as the correct one when examined for reasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Abdoulrab v Ontario (Labour Relations Board)</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 491</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 9</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>59. In the particular context of statutory interpretation, the Court cannot substitute its view of the interpretation and application of the statute for that of the OMDC's reasonably held view. The Supreme Court of Canada articulated this view forcefully in <CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>At the outset it is helpful to contrast judicial review according to the standard of reasonableness with the fundamentally different process of reviewing a decision for correctness. When undertaking a correctness review, the court may undertake its own reasoning process to arrive at the result it judges correct. In contrast, <EM>when deciding whether an administrative action was unreasonable, a court should not at any point ask itself what the correct decision would have been</EM>. Applying the standard of reasonableness gives effect to the legislative intention that a specialized body will have the primary responsibility of deciding the issue according to its own process and for its own reasons. <EM>The standard of reasonableness does not imply that a decision-maker is merely afforded a &ldquo;margin of error&rdquo; around what the court believes is the correct result</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v Ryan</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 20</CITE><PARANUM>50</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Ta b 8</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>No Deference was granted to the OMDC's Interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> and Decision</TI>
<P>60. The OMDC is a specialized agency with expertise in the interpretation and application of the relevant statutory provisions. The question of whether the &ldquo;primary purpose&rdquo; of a promotional game is to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user&rdquo; is a question of law and fact and is at the core of the OMDC's function.</P>
<P>61. In this case, the OMDC determined that the sweepstakes games were developed primarily as promotional vehicles for selling phone cards. This decision was reasonably made having considered each of the sweepstakes games while in operation from the user's perspective, and the developer's intention when developing the games. This conclusion was intelligible and justified based on the wording of the <EM>Regulation</EM>, intent of the <EM>Act</EM>, and on the materials submitted by Pong Marketing.</P>
<P>62. The majority's decision did not examine whether the OMDC's decision fell within a range of possible outcomes. Instead, the majority substituted their interpretation of s. 34(1) for that of the OMDC, and ignored evidence showing that the OMDC did consider the promotional content of the products presented to the users while in operation.</P>
<P>63. On its review of the application, the OMDC concluded that Pong Marketing developed the sweepstakes games to be used as promotional platforms by a licensee to promote products to the end user of the game. As found by the OMDC, Pong Marketing's template licensing agreement and website content demonstrates how Pong Marketing anticipated the sweepstakes games would be used by the licensee.</P>
<P>64. On the basis of its application materials, it was reasonable for the OMDC to conclude that the games were designed by Pong Marketing to be used as loyalty platform software by licensees, to market their products (i.e., phone cards) to the user.</P>
<P>65. The OMDC also considered the promotional content of each of the 15 sweepstakes games while in operation from the user's perspective. The OMDC's correspondence to Pong Marketing, dated October 28, 2015, sets out in detail the OMDC's observations; regarding the promotional content as it appears to users in each of the sweepstakes games.</P>
<P>66. The OMDC concluded that its assessment of the sweepstakes games supports its decision that their primary purpose is to promote the sale of calling cards.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Correspondence through the OAP from the OMDC to Pong Marketing, October 23, 2015, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 6, pp 757&ndash;761</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This decision is entitled to deference, especially since it did include a review of the promotional content in the games themselves which the majority failed to acknowledge.</P>
<P>67. It is important to note that the OMDC's interpretation and application of s. 34(1) does not assume that users cannot be entertained when operating Pong Marketing's products. As noted in dissent, the legislation specifically contemplates that products can serve multiple purposes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 27, para 85</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, the Legislature delegated responsibility to the OMDC to use its expertise in the subject matter and in its interpretation of its home statute to administer the tax credit. Where it has done so reasonably, as it has here, the OMDC is entitled to deference.</P>
<P>68. By failing to consider whether the OMDC's interpretation was justifiable, transparent, and intelligible based on the materials submitted by Pong Marketing, the majority failed to review the decision on a reasonableness standard and instead erroneously applied a standard of correctness. Where the expertise of the OMDC is engaged, as it is here, deference must be granted and respect given to the Legislature's decision to leave such matters in the hands of the OMDC to draw on its particular expertise and experience.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>[2008] 1 SCR 190</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 6</BOLD> (excerpt)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI><UNDER>No Residual Presumption Applies in the Circumstances of the Present Case</UNDER></TI>
<P>69. The majority further erred in finding that the residual presumption in favour of taxpayers would have any application in this case and that it would favour Pong Marketing. The Supreme Court of Canada has held that the residual presumption has a limited purpose and must only be applied in &ldquo;exceptional&rdquo; cases. This is not the case where the residual presumption applies.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>i.</N><TI>The Residual Presumption Applies only in Exceptional Circumstances</TI>
<P>70. There is no longer any rule of statutory interpretation that requires ambiguities in tax-related statutes to be read in favour of taxpayers. If there are two interpretations, the more reasonable one must prevail. When there are two interpretations and one cannot be said to be the more reasonable than the other, the choice should then be resolved in favour of the taxpayer.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ontario Cancer Institute (c.o.b. Princess Margaret Hospital) v Ontario (Minister of Revenue)</SOC><CITE>[1997] OJ No 3446</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Ct. (Gen. Div.)</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 59, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 10</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>71. Where the residual presumption applies, its application is limited to &ldquo;exceptional&rdquo; circumstances. In <CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court explained the limitation of the residual presumption as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[...] first, recourse to the presumption in the taxpayer's favour is indicated when a court is compelled to choose between two valid interpretations, and second, this <BOLD>presumption</BOLD> is <BOLD>clearly residual</BOLD> and should play an exceptional part in the interpretation of tax legislation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</SOC><CITE>[1994] 3 SCR 3</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 11</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>72. More recently, in <CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC><CITE>[2006] 1 SCR 715</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 12</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, the Supreme Court cited <EM>Notre-Dame de Bon Secours</EM> with approval and further described the exceptional role that the residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer plays in the interpretation of taxation statutes:
<QUOTE><P>[...] Any doubt about the meaning of a taxation statute must be reasonable, and no recourse to the presumption lies unless the usual rules of interpretation have been applied, <UNDER>to no avail</UNDER>, in an attempt to discern the meaning of the provision at issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Placer Dome Canada Ltd. v Ontario (Minister of Finance)</SOC><CITE>[2006] 1 SCR 715</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 12</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii.</N><TI>There is No Ambiguity in the Interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation Warranting Application of the Residual Presumption</TI>
<P>73. The majority erred in their application of the residual presumption in the circumstances of this case. In their reasons, the majority declined to resort to the residual presumption because they found on an application of the ordinary rules of interpretation that the OMDC's interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> was unreasonable.</P>
<P>74. Yet, the majority held in the alternative, that even if the OMDC's interpretation is also reasonable<SUP>55</SUP>, the application of the residual presumption requires the Court to favour the interpretation which is more favourable to Pong Marketing.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 19, para 43</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In this circumstance, the application of the residual presumption is incongruent with the principles governing judicial review on a reasonableness standard of review where a decision has been held to be reasonable.</P>
<P>75. In <CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court held that where there are two reasonable competing interpretations of a decision-maker's home statute, the reviewing court must side with the decision-maker:
<QUOTE><P>The bottom line here, then, is that the Commission holds the interpretative upper hand: under reasonableness review, we defer to <EM>any</EM> reasonable interpretation adopted by an administrative decision maker, <EM>even if</EM> other reasonable interpretations may exist. Because the legislature charged the administrative decision maker rather than the courts with &ldquo;administer[ing] and apply[ing]&rdquo; its home statute (<EM>Pezim</EM>, at p. 596), it is the decision maker, first and foremost, that has the discretion to resolve a statutory uncertainty by adopting any interpretation that the statutory language can reasonably bear. Judicial deference in such; instances is itself a principle of modern statutory interpretation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] 3 SCR 895</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 7</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis original]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>76. Because deference is owed to the decision-maker, the applicant has the high burden of proving not only that their interpretation is reasonable, but that the decision-maker's interpretation is <EM>unreasonable</EM>. The Supreme Court framed the applicant's burden this way:
<QUOTE><P>Accordingly, the appellant's burden here is not only to show that her competing interpretation is reasonable, but also that the Commission's interpretation is <EM>unreasonable</EM>. And that she has not done. Here, the Commission, with the benefit of its expertise, chose the interpretation it did. And because that interpretation has not been shown to be an unreasonable one, there is no basis for us to interfere on judicial review&mdash;even in the face of a competing reasonable interpretation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>McLean v British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>[2013] 3 SCR 895</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>OMDC BOA, Tab 7</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>77. Therefore, the majority's resort to the residual presumption where they have found the OMDC's decision to be reasonable stands at odds with both the principles underlying the residual presumption, as well as the well-established administrative law principles guiding the reasonableness standard of review.</P>
<P>78. For this reason, Sachs J. properly discredited the majority's reliance on the residual presumption on the basis that the OMDC's decision is reasonable. Upon restating the &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; role played by the residual presumption, Sachs J. held that because the OMDC was able to ascertain a reasonable interpretation of s. 34(1), the presumption has no application in this case and should not be granted in favour of Pong Marketing. In her dissent, Sachs J. writes:
<QUOTE><P><CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v. Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon-Secours</SOC><CITE>1994 CanLII 58</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1994] 3 S.C.R. 3</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>171 N.R. 161</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> and the cases that have followed it have made it clear that the presumption at issue now has a very limited role to play in the interpretation of tax legislation. It is a residual presumption that should only be resorted to if it is not possible to resolve the meaning of the legislation by applying Driedger's modem approach to statutory interpretation. In this case, the OMDC was able to resolve the meaning of the legislation in question without resort to the residual presumption. A reasonableness review requires that the OMDC's decision in this regard be respected unless it falls outside the range of possible and acceptable outcomes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court Decision, <BOLD>OMDC MR, Tab 3, p 28, para 88</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>79. Accordingly, the majority erroneously held that the residual presumption would be applied in Pong Marketing's favour having found that the OMDC's interpretation of the <EM>Regulation</EM> was reasonable. This holding conflicts with the scope of the reviewing court's authority on a reasonableness standard of review and does not give rise to. the exceptional circumstances necessary to apply the residual presumption.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI><UNDER>It is Both Desirable and in the Public Interest to Grant Leave to Appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>80. Pursuant to Rule.61.03.1, it is both desirable and in the public interest for leave to be granted in this case. The proposed appeal raises many issues of general importance, including the following:
<P1>(a) The <EM>Act</EM> is a statute of general application and interest in the proper interpretation of taxation legislation extends to the general public.</P1>
<P1>(b) The proposed appeal concerns what factors the OMDC can review for future OIDMTC applications, which in turn affects how employers in the cultural media sector will arrange their affairs to benefit from the tax credit and thus continue to create employment opportunities.</P1>
<P1>(c) The proposed appeal examines the appropriate degree of deference that should be afforded to administrative decision makers' interpretation of taxation statutes and examines the intersection between the reasonableness standard of review and the application of the residual presumption.</P1></P>
<P>81. For the foregoing reasons, the OMDC submits that the issues set out above are arguable and of general public importance. They involve the interpretation of an <EM>Act</EM> and <EM>Regulation</EM> and fits within the criteria established by this court in <EM>Sault Dock Company and Limited and Joseph LaRue</EM> as grounds upon which leave may be granted.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART 5&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>82. The OMDC respectfully requests:
<P1>(a) An order granting leave to appeal from the Judgment;</P1>
<P1>(b) The costs of this motion; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
