<BLOCK0><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDING PARTY</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>1)</N><TI>Overview</TI>
<P>1. The Ontario Media Development Corporation (&ldquo;OMDC&rdquo; or &ldquo;the Moving Party&rdquo;) spends most of its factum attempting to convince this Court that the Divisional Court erred in rejecting the OMDC's position. The Divisional Court did not err. Regardless, the ultimate merits of the OMDC's position is not the most important consideration on this motion. The central question for the Court at this stage is whether this case raises an issue of public importance that warrants the consumption of further judicial resources. It does not. Accordingly, the Moving Party's request for leave to appeal should be denied.</P>
<P>2. On any assessment the decision below was a fact-driven application of a narrow statutory provision to an idiosyncratic set of circumstances. The parties are largely in agreement on the well-established and uncontroversial legal principles applied by the Divisional Court. The proposed appeal engages no broader public importance and a second review of the OMDC decision appeal is unwarranted.</P>
<P>3. Indeed, it is well established that where, as here, &ldquo;... the resolution of the question would largely have <BOLD><EM>significance only to the parties and would not settle for the future a question of general interest to the public or a broad segment of the public</EM>,</BOLD> the requirements to obtain leave will not have been met.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Sault Dock Co. v. Sault Ste. Marie (City)</SOC><CITE>[1972] OJ. No. 2069</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at p. 2, Moving Party's Book of Authorities [&ldquo;MPBOA&rdquo;], Tab 1. (emphasis added)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>4. The OMDC's factum evidences demonstrates the narrow implications of the present case. It rehearses its arguments from the court below and emphasizes the dissenting judgment in the Divisional Court which supports the Moving Party's position, but does not show why this case has broader public importance.</P>
<P>5. In any event, the majority of the Divisional Court decision was right. Their decision was based on s. 34(1) of O. Reg. 37/09 (&ldquo;the Regulations&rdquo;); the OMDC's interpretation of that provision was considered and properly rejected. Even if the proposed appeal engaged any broader issues of statutory interpretation or policy there is plainly no basis to disturb the Divisional Court's conclusion.</P>
<P>6. The Responding Party accepts as substantially correct the facts set out in the Moving Party's Factum and relies upon the following additional facts.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>2)</N><TI>Pong's Business Model</TI>
<P>7. Pong Game Studios Corporation (previously Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc.) (&ldquo;Pong&rdquo; or &ldquo;the Respondent&rdquo;) is a digital studio based in Ontario that designs interactive digital games. The Respondent's library of games includes the fifteen &ldquo;sweepstakes&rdquo; games at issue here (&ldquo;the Gaming Products&rdquo;). These games are slot-machine type games in which the player typically has a number of spins. The Gaming Products have creative designs and unique themes that make them fun for the user.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Descriptions of the Gaming Products, including pictures, may be found in the Moving Party's Motion Record [&ldquo;MPMR&rdquo;], Tab 6, pp. 641&ndash;739. In addition, a printout from Pong's website, which gives examples from its current library of games (including some of the Gaming Products), is included in the Responding Party's Motion Record [&ldquo;RPMR&rdquo;], Tab 1. (It may also be found online at <UNDER>http://pongstudios.com/products.html</UNDER>)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. Pong obtains revenue from the Gaming Products by licensing them to third parties, such as telecommunication companies. These third parties use the Gaming Products to promote their own products. Because Pong's games are entertaining to play, they are conducive to providing this promotional opportunity. That is always going to be the case with digital games. As the producers of The Price is Right (or any other game show) would attest, games that are entertaining tend to serve as a good vehicle for promotion.</P>
<P>9. All of Pong's revenue, however, is derived from having users play and enjoy the game. Entertainment is therefore Pong's focus; promotion potential is secondary and completely under the control of the third-party licensee.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>3)</N><TI>The Digital Media Tax Credit</TI>
<P>10. The Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit (&ldquo;Digital Media Tax Credit&rdquo;) was introduced in 1998. It was designed to create &ldquo;good-paying jobs in the high-tech industries&rdquo; such as interactive digital media.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario, Legislative Assembly, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 36th Parl, 2nd Sess, No L064B (3 Dec 1998) at 2020 (Bert Johnson), RPMR, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The aim behind the Digital Media Tax Credit was thus to &ldquo;help businesses in these industries grow and contribute to the development of long-term, internationally viable Ontario industries with jobs for the future.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>. at 2120.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Digital Media Tax Credit was expanded in 2006, 2008, and 2009 with the aim to &ldquo;encourage individuals to invest&rdquo; in the area of digital media.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See</EM> Ontario, Legislative Assembly, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 38th Parl, 2nd Sess, No L116A (31 Oct 2006) at 1630 (Hon Michael A Brown), RPMR, Tab 3. <EM>See also</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Pong Marketing and Promotions Inc. v. Ontario Media Development Corporation</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 434</CITE></CASEREF>, MPMR, Tab 3, at para. 12 [&ldquo;Divisional Court's Reasons&rdquo;].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. Pursuant to s. 34(1) of the Regulations, a &ldquo;non-specified&rdquo; product may eligible for the Digital Media Credit if it is &ldquo;an interactive digital media product&rdquo; and the product is not captured by one of the listed exceptions in s. 34(3). Subsection 34(3) in relevant part provides:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(3)</N><SSECP>A product... is an eligible product for [a credit] if the following conditions are satisfied:
<PARA><N>1.</N><PARAP>The product is an interactive digital media product. ...</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>5.</N><PARAP>The product is not used primarily to present or promote <UNDER>the qualifying corporation or a qualifying predecessor corporation</UNDER>.</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>6.</N><PARAP>The product is not used primarily to present, promote or sell the products or services of <UNDER>the qualifying corporation or of a qualifying predecessor corporation</UNDER>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Emphasis added. Note that the Regulations, including s. 34(3), have recently been amended as of March 14, 2017. The quoted provision is the one that was in force when Pong applied for the Digital Media Tax Credit.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. Thus, an interactive digital media product will not be eligible for the Digital Media Tax Credit if its primary use is to promote <UNDER>the applicant</UNDER> or <UNDER>the applicant's products</UNDER>. The provision contains no reference to the promotion of a third party's products.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>4)</N><TI>OMDC's guidelines and the evolution of the Digital Media Tax Credit</TI>
<P>13. The OMDC has published Guidelines related to the Digital Media Tax Credit. The Guidelines explain, among other things, how eligibility for the credit is determined.</P>
<P>14. The OMDC amended the Guidelines in or around June 2015 in light of proposed amendments to the Regulations (which ultimately went into effect in March 2017). The amended Guidelines also provided additional clarity on the eligibility requirements. The Guidelines explained that products would be considered primarily promotional <UNDER>unless</UNDER> they had a &ldquo;revenue generating stream&rdquo;. According to the OMDC, revenue generating streams include:
<ITEM><P>The sale of the product;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD>Fees for use of the product, including licence and subscription fees; In-product purchases (also called an in-game or in-app purchase, which occurs when the user can purchase an enhancement to the product);</BOLD></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD>Third party advertising within the product (marketing and promotion of a corporation or person, or products or services of a corporation or person, that is not related to the product developer or the purchaser corporation in the case of a specified product);</BOLD> and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The sale or licence of another product developed by your company that can reasonably be considered an extension or upgrade of the product.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario Interactive Digital Media Tax Credit (OIDMTC) Guidelines (updated June 2015), RPMR, Tab 4 (emphasis added).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></ITEM></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>5)</N><TI>Application of the Digital Media Tax Credit to other digital media companies</TI>
<P>15. In light of these Guidelines, the OMDC has granted entitlement to the Digital Media Tax Credit to companies that, like Pong, produce digital games that promote the products of third-party licensees. Fuel Industries (&ldquo;Fuel&rdquo;) is one example. Fuel has benefited from at least $3 million in credits from the OMDC.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario, Legislative Assembly, Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs, <EM>Official Report of Debates (Hansard)</EM>, 41st Parl, 1st Sess, F-9 (22 January 2015) (Hon Sue Wong) at F-144. (<EM>See generally</EM> F-142-44), RPMR, Tab 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> According to its website, Fuel &ldquo;helps Fortune 500 global brands connect with GenZ, Millennial and Family audiences using deep, digital brand experiences that include immersive virtual worlds, mobile apps and social gaming, branded entertainment, interactive multi-screen experiences, interactive rich media advertising, and digital loyalty programs.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fuel Industries, &ldquo;About&rdquo;, online: <UNDER>http://www.fuelyouth.com/about</UNDER>, RPMR, Tab 6A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Fuel's games include such offerings as <EM>NASCAR: Acceleration Nation, Disney Junior Magic Phone, DreamWorks DreamPlace: Naughty or Nice</EM>, and <EM>McDonald's: Cut the Rope</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fuel Industries, &ldquo;Work&rdquo;, online: <UNDER>http://www.fuelyouth.com/work</UNDER>, RPMR, Tab 6B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Fuel boasts on its website that one of its games, available through McDonald's &ldquo;Magic Camera&rdquo; application, &ldquo;led to a 500% increase of the Magic Camera app downloads vs the previous month.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fuel Industries, &ldquo;How to Train Your Dragon 2&rdquo;, online: <UNDER>http://www.fuelyouth.com/projects/how-to-train-yourdragon-2/,</UNDER> RPMR, Tab 6C.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. Fuel was undoubtedly awarded eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit because its games are designed for entertainment and its products have an independent revenue generating stream; moreover, the (extensive) promotional content in Fuel's games is aimed at promoting the products of a third party, not Fuel's own products. Fuel, like Pong, is not excluded by any of the listed exceptions in s. 34(3).</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>6)</N><TI>Pong's Application for the Digital Media Tax Credit</TI>
<P>17. Pong applied for the Digital Media Tax Credit for the Gaming Products on April 16, 2014. Pong sought a tax credit of approximately $2 million. The claimed amount represented the work of over 60 Pong game developers, testers, mathematicians, and designers, constituting 90% of Pong's employees at the time.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See</EM> Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 4; <EM>see also</EM> MPMR, Tab 6, at p. 768.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. Pong expended significant resources developing the Gaming Products on the expectation that it would, according to the plain meaning of the relevant provision, receive the Digital Media Tax Credit. Pong was anxious to receive these funds in order to reinvest in its business and employ additional people at its Woodbridge, Ontario facility.</P>
<P>19. On December 11, 2015, almost <UNDER>two years</UNDER> after its application was submitted, the OMDC notified the Respondent that its application had been denied.</P>
<P>20. The decision was conveyed in a brief letter from the OMDC's Director of Tax Credits and Financing Programs. The letter stated, in conclusory terms, that the products did not satisfy s. 34(1) of the Digital Media Tax Credit Regulations because their primary purpose was not to &ldquo;educate, inform or entertain the user.&rdquo; Rather, the OMDC concluded the primary purpose of the products was &ldquo;to promote the sale of phonecards and other related products and services.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter from J. Blitz to W. Dawson (Dec. 11, 2015), MPMR, Tab 5, p. 37.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;POSITION ON ISSUES</TI>
<P>21. The Moving Party proposes three issues.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Moving Party's Factum, at para. 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Properly understood the present motion presents the following questions:
<P1>(a) Did the Divisional Court err in concluding that, according to the plain meaning of s. 34(1) of the Regulations, the &ldquo;primary purpose&rdquo; of the Gaming Products is to entertain the user?</P1>
<P1>(b) Does this appeal raise issues of public importance such that this Honourable Court should take the exceptional step of granting leave to appeal a decision of the Divisional Court?</P1></P>
<P>22. The issues raised by the appeal proposed by the Moving Party are in no sense of public importance and do not disclose the sort of uncertainty in the jurisprudence that might justify the unusual step of a second level of review. Regardless, the Divisional Court was right and its decision should not be disturbed. Leave should be refused.</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Did the Divisional Court err in concluding that, according to the plain meaning of s. 34(1) of O. Reg 37/09, the &ldquo;primary purpose&rdquo; of the Gaming Products is to entertain the user?</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>1)</N><TI>The Divisional Court's application of s. 34(1) of the Regulations to the facts of this case was correct.</TI>
<P>23. The Moving Party argues that the Divisional Court's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulation &ldquo;is too narrow and reads in limitations to the scope of the provision that undermine legislative intent.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Moving Party's Factum, at para. 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> With respect, this is the pot calling the kettle black. The Divisional Court's interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulations is the only reasonable interpretation available in light of the plain language of the provision and the object and purpose behind the Digital Media Tax Credit. In contrast, the OMDC's interpretation is ungrounded in the words of the Regulations and calculated to contrive an overly restrictive reading that clashes with the language of the provision and its legislative purpose.</P>
<P>24. The Divisional Court examined the plain language of s. 34(1), which defines an &ldquo;interactive digital media product&rdquo; as:
<QUOTE><P>... <EM>a combination of</EM> one or more <EM>application files</EM> and one or more <EM>data files</EM>, all in a digital format, that are integrated and are intended to be operated together and <EM>that have the following characteristics when they are being operated:</EM></P>
<P>1. <UNDER><EM>Their</EM></UNDER> primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 26 (underlining added by Divisional Court; other emphasis added).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>25. The Divisional Court rightly pointed out that the &ldquo;their&rdquo; in s. 34(1) of the Regulations obviously refers to the &ldquo;application files&rdquo; or the &ldquo;data files&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>. at para. 27.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Put simply, the provision indicates that a digital game will be an interactive digital media product if the primary purpose of <UNDER>the game</UNDER>, <UNDER>while it is being played</UNDER>, is to entertain <UNDER>the user</UNDER>. No other reasonable reading of the Regulations is credibly available. Had the Regulations intended to focus on the developer, it could have, and would have, said so.</P>
<P>26. As the Divisional Court summarized (at para. 33):
<QUOTE><P>The definition focuses on the time when the application files and data files are operated together by the user and provides that one of their characteristics at that moment is that their primary purpose is to educate, inform or entertain the user. The only time the user operates those files is when he or she is playing a Sweepstakes game. The primary purpose of the applicant when creating or licensing the product is a different inquiry.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>27. In addition to emphasizing the unambiguous language of the provision, the Divisional Court explained why the OMDC's interpretation clashes with the object and purpose behind the Digital Media Tax Credit.</P>
<P>28. The OMDC felt that the primary purpose of the Gaming Products was not to entertain the user because the games were designed to, among other things, &ldquo;help licensees or retailers compete against top competitors in the phone card market&rdquo; and &ldquo;create consumer involvement with a brand or product to encourage consumption of that product.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>. at para. 30.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. That reading of the provision is simply unreasonable and ungrounded in the words. Whatever measure of deference one offers to the OMDC, at some point words have obvious meanings that must be respected. The OMDC's approach is unsustainable.</P>
<P>30. It flies in the face of the Digital Media Tax Credit's entire reason for existence: to create jobs in Ontario in the digital media industry.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See</EM> Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 36.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong creates digital games that are entertaining. It employs dozens of people and expends significant resources in the development process. Pong's underlying motivation is, of course, to create profit by selling or licensing its games to third parties. That is the case with all for-profit entities.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See id</EM>. at para. 40:
<QUOTE><P>The respondent submitted that the Ontario Media Development Corporation has a cultural aspect to it&mdash;a submission with which I agree. I recognize that the digital media tax credit is available to not-for-profit arts and cultural enterprises. I also recognize that those corporations do not have a profit motive. I do not believe this makes any difference to the proper interpretation of the regulation. The tax credit was introduced to benefit or assist the development of the interactive digital media industry. At the same time tax credits were introduced to benefit sound recording, computer animation and special effects companies and thereby create jobs in Ontario. The inclusion of not-for-profit arts and cultural enterprises was not accompanied by a corresponding restriction on the availability of this credit to for-profit corporations.</P></QUOTE></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong's games are attractive to third parties <BOLD><EM>because they entertain</EM></BOLD> and therefore offer an effective vehicle for the promotion of their products.</P>
<P>31. Furthermore, in licensing its games to third parties, Pong (like Fuel, above) is also complying with a <UNDER>pre-requisite</UNDER> for eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit as set out in the OMDC's Guidelines&mdash;namely, that the product have a revenue generating stream. The Guidelines explicitly indicate that revenue generating streams may include licensing fees for use of the product and third party advertising within the product, which may come from promotion of the third party and/or the third party's products. In fact, without a revenue generating stream, the OMDC has indicated that it will consider the product to be primarily promotional. The OMDC cannot reasonably mandate that the product have a revenue generating stream and then punish the applicant for marketing its product in a way that derives revenue.</P>
<P>32. The OMDC's interpretation would create the perverse situation where digital gaming companies are forced to choose between licensing opportunities and eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit. That approach would actually <EM>discourage</EM> investment in the digital media field. Such an interpretation would defeat the purpose behind the Digital Media Tax Credit and is absurd. It is, therefore, unreasonable.</P>
<P>33. Indeed, as Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O. noted for the majority of the Divisional Court, it is nonsensical to cite the developer's profit-making motive as a reason for disqualifying it from the tax credit:
<QUOTE><P>A developer intending to license games will primarily want the games to promote the product of the licensee otherwise the licensee will not want the games. The respondent's reliance on this motivation or statements of it to conclude that the developer's product is primarily promotional and therefore not eligible for the tax credit means that the developer's fundamental purpose weighs negatively against eligibility for the tax credit, even though the legislature intended to use the tax credit to assist high-technology, knowledge-based industries.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, para. 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>34. Thus, in denying Pong's application for the Digital Media Tax Credit, the OMDC conflated Pong's <UNDER>business model</UNDER> with its <UNDER>products' purpose</UNDER>. Pong develops its games to be entertaining to the user. Once developed, however, Pong must sell or license the games in order to derive revenue from them. Without revenue, it cannot create jobs.</P>
<P>35. The OMDC claims that the Divisional Court erred by focusing on the user's purpose for playing the games instead of the developer's purpose for developing the games. It says the user's purpose is less important because it &ldquo;will always be subjective&rdquo; and therefore difficult to pin down; the developer's purpose, in contrast, is discernable through, for example, the developer's promotional materials.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See</EM> Moving Party's Factum, at para. 50.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This does not make sense, and in any event does not come close to what the section actually says.</P>
<P>36. The user's purpose for playing Pong's digital games is not nebulous. It is obvious: users play the games to be entertained. Users do not play the games for their promotional content; the promotional content is placed in the game by a third party seeking to take advantage of the user's captivated attention.</P>
<P>37. Every developer's motivation is fixed: it is to derive revenue from the games. That is why the Regulations' language focuses on the user, not the developer. Focusing on the developer would mean that only not-for-profit product development would qualify for the credit. But that would render the Digital Media Tax Credit unobtainable (because of the requirement of revenue).</P>
<P>38. The OMDC contends that under the Divisional Court's interpretation of the provision &ldquo;all interactive digital media products, and in particular all digital interactive games, regardless of their predominant purpose, would qualify.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>. at para. 52.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This concern is without merit and easily dismissed. There is a litany of digital media products that would not be eligible for the tax credit because their primary purpose while being operated is not to &ldquo;educate, inform, or entertain&rdquo; the user. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Venngo Inc. v. Ontario Media Development Corp.</SOC><CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 961</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, the Divisional Court upheld the OMDC's ruling that a coupon website did not qualify for the Digital Media Tax Credit. Nor would every digital game qualify. The legislature has placed express limits on eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit by, for example, excluding products that promote the applicant's <UNDER>own</UNDER> products or services.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See</EM> s. 34(3) of the Regulations, <EM>supra</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> And, most significantly, as the Divisional Court pointed out, <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;[i]f the [OMDC] thinks that the regulation, properly interpreted, is not achieving the intended objective or is overly generous, then it is open to the Government to amend the regulation</EM>,&rdquo;</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 39 (emphasis added).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. The government has, in fact, recently amended the Regulation and narrowed eligibility for the Digital Media Tax Credit. That is within its prerogative. It is <UNDER>not</UNDER>, however, open to the Moving Party to move the Court to retroactively read in limitations that did not exist at the relevant time.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>2)</N><TI>The Divisional Court applied a reasonableness standard of review and granted deference to the OMDC.</TI>
<P>40. The Moving Party argues that the Divisional Court did not &ldquo;grant deference to the OMDC's interpretation of its home statute, and in doing so, erroneously appl[ied] a standard of correctness.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Moving Party's Factum, at para. 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This assertion is groundless.</P>
<P>41. The Divisional Court applied a standard of reasonableness to the OMDC's decision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, para. 24.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Quoting from <EM>Venngo</EM>, the Court found that the interpretation of s. 34(1) of the Regulations is &ldquo;a question that concerns OMDC's interpretation of its home legislation and is exactly the type of issue that falls within the OMDC's specialized expertise. The question ... lies at the core of the OMDC's function.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>., quoting <EM>Venngo</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. The problem is that the OMDC's reading of the provision was unreasonable. Deference does not mean a body like the OMDC is a law unto itself. It remains subject to review. In approaching the OMDC's decision the Court referenced <CASEREF><SOC>Law Society of New Brunswick v. Ryan</SOC></CASEREF>, which states that &ldquo;an unreasonable decision [i]s one that did not stand up to a somewhat probing analysis.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2003 SCC 20, at para. 25, MPBOA, Tab 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Court conducted such an analysis and rightly concluded that the OMDC's decision could not withstand somewhat probing scrutiny.</P>
<P>43. What the OMDC really takes issue with is the fact that the Divisional Court found its decision to be unreasonable. That complaint is unfounded.</P>
<P>44. A reasonableness standard accords deference to an administrative body's decisions; it does not <UNDER>immunize</UNDER> all decisions made by that administrative body. Here, the Divisional Court applied the correct standard of review and found that the OMDC's application of the Regulations in these circumstances was unreasonable. There is no basis to interfere with that finding.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>3)</N><TI>The Divisional Court's discussion of the residual presumption was strictly <EM>obiter</EM> and played no role in the decision below.</TI>
<P>45. The Moving Party argues that the majority of the Divisional Court erred by &ldquo;[m]isapplying the residual presumption to the circumstances of this case.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, para. 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This contention is also baseless.</P>
<P>46. The residual presumption states that &ldquo;a reasonable doubt, not resolved by the ordinary rules of interpretation,&rdquo; regarding the applicability of a tax credit &ldquo;will be settled by recourse to [a] residual presumption in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Id</EM>. at para. 43, quoting <CASEREF><SOC>Qu&ea;bec (Communaut&ea; urbaine) v. Corp. Notre-Dame de Bon-Secours</SOC><CITE>[1994] 3 S.C.R. 3</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>, MPBOA, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>47. As a preliminary matter, the Divisional Court did not <UNDER>apply</UNDER> the residual presumption. It therefore could not have <UNDER>mis</UNDER>applied it. The majority's reasons were very clear that it was <UNDER>not</UNDER> resorting to the residual presumption, due to its conclusion that the OMDC's decision was unreasonable. Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O. was unambiguous on this point; as he wrote: &ldquo;I do not find it necessary to resort to this principle to resolve this application because I do not think the respondent's interpretation is a reasonable one.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Divisional Court's Reasons, at para. 43.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>48. In any event, the parties are essentially <EM>ad idem</EM> on the applicability of the residual presumption. The OMDC writes that &ldquo;[w]hen there are two interpretations and one cannot be said to be the more reasonable than the other, the choice should then be resolved in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Moving Party's Factum, at para. 70.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Pong agrees with this statement and so would Marrocco A.C.J.S.C.O.</P>
<P>49. The real point of disagreement between the Moving Party and the Respondent is whether the OMDC's decision was reasonable. Imagine for a moment that the OMDC's reading is one of the reasonable readings of the Regulations. The Court would then be faced with a situation in which there are <EM>two competing reasonable interpretations</EM>. In that situation, as the OMDC admits, &ldquo;the choice should [] be resolved in favour of the taxpayer.&rdquo; Accordingly, Pong would still be entitled to the Digital Media Tax Credit.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>Does this appeal raise issues of public importance such that this Honourable Court should take the exceptional step of granting leave to appeal a decision of the Divisional Court?</TI>
<P>50. Nothing about the appeal as framed by the Moving Party calls for any consideration of the law that could have broader implications for the justice system or the governing jurisprudence. There is nothing to suggest other cases will be directly or indirectly impacted by the issues proposed here. At best, the concerns raised by the Moving Party are strictly limited to the facts of this case, and, therefore, do not meet the test for granting leave to appeal. And, more to the point&mdash;<BOLD><EM>if related to the reading of the Regulations, it is entirely within the power of the government to amend the Regulations</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>51. An appeal to the Court of Appeal from a decision of the Divisional Court is intended to be extraordinary (thus the requirement that a party obtain leave of the court).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>See, e.g., Sault Dock Co</EM>., <EM>supra</EM>, at p. 2; <CASEREF><SOC>Enbridge Gas Distribution Inc. v. Froese</SOC><CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 896</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 19, Responding Party's Book of Authorities [&ldquo;RPBOA&rdquo;], Tab 1; <CASEREF><SOC>Reid v. College of Chiropractors of Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2016] O.J. No. 5450</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 19, RPBOA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The primary consideration on a motion for leave to appeal in such a case is whether the proposed appeal raises important issues deserving of consideration by this Court. In answering this question the Court will consider a number of factors, including:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ontario (Minister of Transportation) v. 1520658 Ontario Inc.</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 32</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF>, RPBOA, Tab 3; <EM>Sault Dock Co</EM>., <EM>supra</EM> at p. 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>a) whether the Divisional Court exercised appellate jurisdiction (in which case the applicant for leave is seeking an extraordinary <EM>second</EM> appeal) or whether the Divisional Court was sitting as a court of original jurisdiction;</P1>
<P1>b) whether the appeal involves the interpretation of a statute or regulation, including its constitutionality;</P1>
<P1>c) whether the appeal involved the interpretation, clarification or propounding of some general rule or principle of law; and</P1>
<P1>d) whether the interpretation of the law or agreement in issue is of significance only to the parties or whether a question of general interest to the public or a broad segment of the public would be settled for the future.</P1></P>
<P>52. The extraordinary step of granting leave to appeal is unjustified because the Divisional Court's decision was largely fact-driven. The factual matrix raised by this case is unique, of limited importance or general interest to the public, and very unlikely to arise again. It is trite law that in such circumstances leave to appeal is unwarranted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Enbridge</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 24.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. Indeed, the Moving Party accepts as correct the legal tests applied by the majority in the Divisional Court. The Moving Party agrees, for example, that the Divisional Court applied the appropriate standard of review. And the Moving Party further agrees with the Divisional Court that the residual presumption has no applicability in this case.</P>
<P>54. The OMDC's point of disagreement is with the manner in which the majority in the Divisional Court applied these uncontroversial legal principles to the distinct facts of this case. That is an insufficient reason to grant a second level of review.</P>
<P>55. For the reasons set out above, the proposed appeal also lacks the sort of merit that might justify the granting of leave. The Divisional Court was correct in its approach and its conclusions related to the the Digital Media Tax Credit that arose on the facts. Leave to appeal should be denied.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ADDITIONAL ISSUES</TI>
<P>56. The Respondent raises no additional issues.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>57. The Respondent respectfully requests that the motion be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P>58. As this is a Motion for Leave to Appeal, no court time is required unless mandated by the Court.</P>
